<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spielberg Wins Award From Guild </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Steven Spielberg won the Directors Guild of  
America's award on Saturday night for ``Saving Private Ryan,'' 
making him and the epic World War II film strong favorites for 
Academy Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	In voting by the union for filmmakers, Spielberg defeated  
Roberto Benigni of ``Life is Beautiful,'' John Madden of 
``Shakespeare in Love,'' Terrence Malick of ``The Thin Red Line,'' 
and Peter Weir of ``The Truman Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I am so happy. I'm like so -- '' Spielberg said, interrupting  
himself as he dropped the plaque onto the podium with a clunk. 
</P>
<P>
	Back stage, Spielberg joked, ``I can't believe I dropped it.''  
</P>
<P>
	He dedicated the award to his father, Arnold Spielberg, and his  
father's World War II generation. 
</P>
<P>
	Spielberg noted that the award came at a time in which all five  
directors were nominated for both DGA awards and Academy Awards for 
historical films, three dealing with the World War II period and 
two with the Elizabethan era. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are finding ways of embracing history,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``Saving Private Ryan,'' which follows a squad of soldiers sent  
to find a private whose brothers were killed in the war, was 
nominated for 11 Academy Awards, second only to ``Shakespeare in 
Love,'' with 13. 
</P>
<P>
	In winning a DGA award, Spielberg stands a strong chance of  
getting a director's award at the Oscars on March 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Only four times has the DGA winner not repeated at the Academy  
Awards. The winner of the directing Oscar also usually sees his 
film take a best picture award. 
</P>
<P>
	Spielberg has won three DGA awards, also getting honors for  
``The Color Purple,'' (1985) and ``Schindler's List,'' (1993). 
``Schindler's List'' went on to win seven Academy Awards, including 
best picture and best director. 
</P>
<P>
	In the DGA's television categories, Paris Barcklay won for the  
emotionally gripping episode of ``NYPD Blue'' in which Jimmy Smits' 
character dies, and Michael Cristofer won for the television movie 
``Gia.'' The documentary DGA award went to the makers of ``Vietnam: 
Long Time Coming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Director's Guild of America represents more than 10,000  
members working in American cities and abroad. Their work is 
represented in theatrical, industrial, educational and documentary 
films as well as television shows, movies and commercials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
