<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Czechs See Hope in Boeing Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- A black-and-white photo on the  
wall of Aero Vodochody's production hangar shows the heyday of the 
Warsaw Pact arms industry -- row after row of sleek MiG fighters 
coming off the line. 
</P>
<P>
	Look around the mostly empty hangar today and see the Czech  
company's contemporary history -- a few light attack planes 
lingering from a busted 1991 deal with Nigeria, and a handful of 
workers who head for their posts when the boss walks in. 
</P>
<P>
	A closer view reveals the future.  
</P>
<P>
	The boss is an American from Boeing Co. who became president  
last year when Boeing bought a 35 percent stake in Aero Vodochody. 
Coming down the production line is the first L159 light fighter 
jet, a Cold War hybrid that mates a Warsaw Pact favorite with 
high-tech Western electronics. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott White, a Californian who jointly runs Aero Vodochody with  
Czech chief executive officer Adam Stranak, explained that Boeing 
bought in to get a share of the Central European market formerly 
closed to the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing considers its investment a strategic move to expand its  
product line and possibly bring more contracts and influence in the 
region, White said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also mentioned the possibility that the partnership with the  
Czech Republic's major airplane maker could boost Boeing's chance 
of winning a big fighter aircraft sale to the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The F-18, produced by Boeing after it took over McDonnell  
Douglas Corp., is considered a front-runner for a possible joint 
purchase by Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to bring their 
air forces to NATO standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Preparing Aero Vodochody to compete on global markets required  
major changes, White said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the Warsaw Pact days, Aero Vodochody ``never had the  
training or the focus to make a profit,'' he said. ``They were 
basically a producer of airplanes. That was it. They didn't have to 
sell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	White said Boeing, despite its minority holding, exerted  
management control by taking three of the five board seats and 
trimming 10 percent of the work force, down to 2,200. It opened 
communications with unions and workers to head off protests over 
the layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not stupid. They understand,'' White said. ``We had  
people standing around not doing anything.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
