<DOCNO> APW19990306.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 05:22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Restructuring Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Air Force is moving to limit overseas  
deployments, setting a new standard of 90 days in every 15 months 
for most service members based in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to take a lot of unpredictability out of people's  
lives,'' Acting Air Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes, to take place no later than next January, are an  
attempt by the Air Force to ease the strain of frequent foreign 
missions, low morale and a troubling exodus of pilots to 
higher-paying airline jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The overhaul, the first major one for the Air Force since the  
end of the Cold War, establishes 10 main ``expeditionary'' groups 
that would rotate responsibility for foreign deployments. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the forces for military-type missions, an  
additional five groups were set up to handle humanitarian missions 
such as last year's delivery of aid to victims of Hurricane Mitch 
in Central America. 
</P>
<P>
	And for the first time, members of the Air Force Reserve and Air  
National Guard would be included among the rotations. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'll still be pulling some travels, you'll still be flying  
jets or whatever you do. But you're going to know when that's going 
to be,'' Peters said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of disillusioned military pilots told a House Armed  
Services subcommittee earlier this week that it wasn't just the 
bigger salaries at airlines that were coaxing them to leave the 
military -- but also poor working conditions and almost constant 
overseas assignments, sometimes coming with only a few days' 
notice. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new structure, Air Force crews would know well in  
advance when they might be sent overseas -- and for how long they'd 
have to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	Peters said almost 70 percent of the 365,000 active-duty  
personnel are married, many with children, a reversal of the force 
during the Vietnam War, when a similar percentage was single. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people are being run pretty ragged,'' he acknowledged.  
</P>
<P>
	For military missions, the new groups are intended to deploy  
anywhere in the world within 48 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Each ``air expeditionary force'' unit will average about 15,000  
people and about 175 planes, including fighter jets and heavy 
bombers, as well as reconnaissance, electronic warfare, refueling 
and transport aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	The aircraft will be based at separate airfields, but air crews  
will train together. Two groups will be on duty at any given time. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10 main ``air expeditionary force'' units will have  
headquarters at the following Air Force bases: Hill, Utah; Dyess, 
Texas; Elmendorf, Alaska; Davis Monthan, Ariz.; Shaw, S.C.; 
Barksdale, La.; Ellsworth, S.D.; Cannon, N.M.; and Langley, Va., as 
well as Lakenheath Air Base in England. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the five units that will focus only on humanitarian  
aid missions have headquarters at these Air Force bases: Pope, 
N.C.; Travis, Calif.; McConnell, Kan.; Grand Forks, N.D.; and 
Fairchild, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	Two additional units, at Mountain Home Air Force Base, Idaho,  
and Seymour Johnson Air Force Base, N.C., would not be part of the 
usual rotation but would remain on call at all times as backup 
units. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force cited as a reason for the overhaul a fourfold jump  
in the number of foreign operations over the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The overhaul also brings the 125,000 people in Air Force Reserve  
and Air National Guard units into the rotation schedule. It would 
not affect those permanently attached to most overseas bases, 
including those in Europe, South Korea and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
