<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kosovo Peace Deal Expected Sunday  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- All factions of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo  
have promised to sign a peace plan that would give them autonomy, 
the Clinton administration said. The pledge, if carried out, would 
intensify pressure on the Serbs to sign or face NATO airstrikes. 
Former Sen. Bob Dole, who negotiated the agreement at the request 
of President Clinton, told Secretary of State Madeleine Albright 
today he was confident Kosovo's Albanians would follow through. 
That would leave the Serbs' refusal to accept NATO's peacekeeping 
role as the main stumbling block when peace talks resume March 15. 

</P>
<P>
	Apparent Haiti Smuggling Boats Sink  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Two apparent smuggling boats sank today off the  
South Florida coast and as many 40 Haitians were missing as the 
Coast Guard searched for survivors. Three men rescued off West Palm 
Beach told U.S. Border Patrol officers that one boat -- carrying 18 
Haitians -- broke down and that the other boat -- carrying between 18 
to 25 more refugees -- came to help out. Both boats then went under, 
they said. ``It's a lot people. Right now, we're looking for 36 to 
40 people,'' Coast Guard spokesman Lt. Ron LaBrec said. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Urges Crackdown on Kurds  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit is urging  
European leaders to crack down on supporters of Kurdish rebels, 
officials said today. Ecevit sent letters on Tuesday to the heads 
of state of both NATO and European Union countries -- except Greece 
-- two weeks after the capture of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah 
Ocalan. Ocalan is the leader of the Kurdistan Workers Party, or 
PKK, whose battles with the government have claimed 37,000 lives in 
the country's southeast since 1984. 

</P>
<P>
	Anti-Sweatshop Protests Staged  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Protesters across the country demonstrated today  
outside stores they say sell clothing made in sweatshop conditions. 
In San Francisco, as many as 300 activists crowded in front of the 
Gap flagship store in the busy downtown shopping district. Police 
arrested 16 after they blocked a doorway to the store, said Capt. 
Dennis Martel. Several hundred activists marched up Manhattan's 
Fifth Avenue in the rain. The New York rally ended in front of the 
Nike store on East 57th Street. 

</P>
<P>
	Protestants, Sinn Fein To Talk  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Ulster Unionist Party leader  
David Trimble said today he has invited the senior Sinn Fein 
leaders to urgent talks, the first time he's done so. Although 
Trimble began talking with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams six months 
ago, until now such contact has always been at the behest of the 
Irish Republican Army-allied party. The invitation comes as the 
deadline set by the British government approaches to hand back 
power to local politicians in accord with last year's peace 
agreement. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Demands Colombian Killers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Colombia rebel group must turn over those  
responsible for the kidnapping and murder of three Americans found 
dead in Venezuela, the White House demanded today. ``We have strong 
indications they were kidnapped and murdered by members of the 
Colombian rebel group'' known as the Revolutionary Armed Force of 
Colombia, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said. The United 
States will help Colombian officials catch the killers, gather 
evidence and see them indicted and convicted, he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Country Singer George Jones Injured  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKLIN, Tenn. (AP) -- Country singer George Jones was in  
critical condition today after being involved in a car accident 
near his home. Jones, 67, was injured at about 3 p.m. when his 
sport-utility vehicle smashed into a bridge abutment on Highway 96. 
He was taken by helicopter to Vanderbilt University Medical Center 
in nearby Nashville. Hospital spokesman Wayne Wood said he did not 
know if the injuries were life-threatening. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 13 Arizona Beats No. 12 UCLA  
</P>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Jason Terry, the Pac-10 player of the year,  
scored 26 points in his final home game, 18 in the first half, as 
13th-ranked Arizona routed No. 12 UCLA 87-70 today in a game that 
decided second place in the conference. Terry hit his last 
homecourt jumper with 1:07 to play, then took a bow and blew kisses 
to the capacity crowd as he left the game with 50.9 seconds to 
play. 

</P>
<P>
	Garth Brooks Leaves Padres Camp  
</P>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ariz. (AP) -- Country singer Garth Brooks abruptly left  
the San Diego Padres training camp, apparently due to a family 
illness, and the club isn't sure when he might return. Club 
officials would only say that Brooks wasn't in camp due to personal 
reasons. The Associated Press learned that Brooks left for Los 
Angeles to be with his mother, who has had cancer. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  

</P>
