<DOCNO> APW19990306.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 09:12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McClatchy Keeping Pirates in Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) -- Kevin McClatchy's biggest accomplishment  
in the three years since major league baseball's youngest owner 
bought one of the sport's oldest teams is they are still called the 
Pittsburgh Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in 1996, after the former newspaper reporter, advertising  
salesman and Giants fan bought the Pirates following seven months 
of laborious negotiations that often threatened to unravel, people 
speculated the team might become the Washington Pirates or the 
Charlotte Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	In baseball, they were guessing which withering-on-the-vine  
small market team would move first: the fan-devoid Montreal Expos 
or the cash-poor Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	``People came up to me as soon as we bought the team and asked  
when we were moving to Sacramento,'' McClatchy said, referring to 
his hometown. ``I said, `Give us a chance first.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the Pirates' future -- in Pittsburgh, no less -- seems  
brighter than it has since they last won the World Series in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	They will break ground next month on a 38,000-seat riverfront  
ballpark that will meld the fan-friendly memories of Forbes Field 
with the revenue-generating aesthetics of luxury boxes and club 
seats necessary to compete in the big-money world of pro sports in 
the 21st century. 
</P>
<P>
	Ticket sales are way up. And the Pirates actually made a modest  
profit the last two seasons, even if it took a massive payroll 
slashing to accomplish it in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were one of the few teams in baseball to make a profit both  
years,'' McClatchy said. ``Considering where we came from, it's an 
accomplishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Where they came from was the brink of extinction in 1995, when  
fans feared the Pirates' last home game that season might be their 
last in Pittsburgh. Major league baseball had rejected cable TV 
entrepreneur John Rigas' offer -- he would later buy the NHL's 
Buffalo Sabres -- and few gave credence to McClatchy's seemingly 
underfinanced attempt to enter the elite group of big corporations 
and billionaires who largely comprise major league ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	McClatchy had plenty of reasons to fail.  
</P>
<P>
	His family owns the newspaper chain of the same name, and  
McClatchy himself is a millionaire. But he did not have the vast 
wads of cash to shower on a team like many club owners do. 
</P>
<P>
	He had failed previously to buy the Oakland Athletics. So when  
he set up shop in a windowless one-room Pittsburgh office lent him 
by a sympathetic lawyer friend in August 1995, McClatchy was given 
as little chance to complete the purchase as the Pirates were of 
winning the pennant. 
</P>
<P>
	But he won over Mayor Tom Murphy, who had made it a priority to  
preserve baseball. He also assembled a score of investors who 
pitched in $1 million or $2 million each and a handful who put up 
$5 million each, including Indy car owner Chip Ganassi. 
</P>
<P>
	By February 1996, McClatchy had himself a baseball team.  
Remarkably, he was only 32 -- younger than some of his players. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people didn't think he could it,'' Murphy said.  
</P>
<P>
	National League president Len Coleman did, quickly embracing  
McClatchy's group and steering it through the difficult approval 
process by fellow owners. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were of a single mind to keep this storied franchise in  
Pittsburgh, this franchise of Wagner, Stargell and Clemente,'' 
Coleman said. ``Kevin McClatchy is a dynamic leader ... who was 
tested throughout this process but proved every time he could keep 
this together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there were fits and starts even after McClatchy bought  
the team -- mostly fits of disappointment and poor starts by his 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	He couldn't afford expensive free agents, which meant the  
on-field product wasn't attractive or successful in 1996. A couple 
of his big investors bailed out after six months, saying the kid 
owner didn't know how to run a team. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Leyland, regarded as one of baseball's best managers,  
triggered an escape clause in his contract, and left to manage 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Patiently, McClatchy sorted out the finances, brought in  
newspaper owner G. Ogden Nutting as a partner and ordered a massive 
payroll slashing that kept the franchise fiscally viable. The idea 
was to rebuild through the farm system in anticipation of fielding 
a winning team once the Pirates moved into a new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, as McClatchy begins his fourth year as a major league club  
owner, the new ballpark is a certainty following a spasmodic 
two-year fight that nearly unraveled numerous times amid political 
infighting and public indifference. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates' challenge no longer is to get a stadium, but to  
build it -- and, they hope, a championship-caliber team to occupy it 
once it opens in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun to be able to concentrate on baseball again,''  
McClatchy said. ``It beats fighting with politicians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New stadium. New players. Hey, isn't that how they did it in  
Cleveland, Baltimore and Texas? 
</P>
<P>
	``Look back at the last three years; I'd say we did all right.  
We did everything we said we were going to do,'' McClatchy said. '' 
We kept the Pirates in Pittsburgh. We're getting a new stadium. 
Strangely enough, after three turbulent years, I still want to run 
a baseball franchise.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
