<HEADLINE> Judge Dismisses Irvin Police Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit Dallas  
Cowboys players Erik Williams and Michael Irvin filed against the 
Dallas police after a woman accused them of sexually assaulting her 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Sidney A. Fitzwater ruled Friday that  
Williams and Irvin failed to prove allegations that police violated 
their civil rights during an investigation into allegations made by 
Nina Shahravan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Shahravan was convicted of perjury after recanting her  
allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	She told police that she had been raped by Williams and an  
unidentified man while Irvin held her at gunpoint and videotaped 
the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	A month later, she admitted to police that Irvin was not present  
and that she willingly had sex with Williams and another man. 
</P>
<P>
	Police cleared the players later that day, and no charges were  
filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Shahravan subsequently pleaded guilty to perjury and served  
a 90-day jail sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams and Irvin sued the city of Dallas, police Chief Ben  
Click, police spokesman Sgt. Jim Chandler, and three officers who 
investigated the allegations by the former topless dancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Ginsburg, a Washington lawyer representing both players,  
said he would appeal Fitzwater's ruling or file new lawsuits in 
state court. 
</P>
<P>
	Several officers named in the suit said they were glad the case  
was over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am pleased that it has been resolved,'' Chandler said  
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
