<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazilian police charged seven officers  
Saturday with the slayings of three young people found with gunshot 
wounds to the head, said a police spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies of the three, ages 14, 17, and 21, were found in a  
forest near Sao Vicente, a coastal town 50 miles southeast of Sao 
Paulo, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The discovery of the dead youths, found close to beaches popular  
with vacationers, has shocked Brazilians. 
</P>
<P>
	The trio disappeared during the nation's annual carnival  
celebrations three weeks ago, but their bodies were only found 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven police officers allegedly drove the victims into the  
forest and shot them, the spokesman said. The officers will be 
tried in a criminal court. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazilian employers cut some  
580,000 jobs in 1998, the highest number in six years, the O Globo 
newspaper reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most jobs were cut last December with service and construction  
industries heavily hit, said the daily, citing Employment Ministry 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministry experts blamed the cuts on high interest rates  
introduced to counter financial turbulence battering Brazil, the 
daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only this week, new Central Bank president Arminio Fraga raised  
interest rates further, from 39 percent to 45 percent, to combat 
inflation. Financial markets reacted well but many economists say 
the move will deepen Brazil's recession. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, only 35,000 jobs were cut by employers in Brazil.  
</P>
<P>
	According to government figures, about 8 percent of the  
country's economically active population of some 50 million are 
jobless, the highest rate since 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A former official of the Gulf coast state of  
Tabasco has accused the state's governor of illegally using tax 
revenues to pay for an ad campaign, authorities said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Emmanuel Ruiz, former general director of the state government  
office, accused Roberto Madrazo of retaining millions of dollars in 
payroll taxes to fund a flashy TV and media campaign touting him 
for the 2000 presidential race, the newspaper La Jornada reported 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruiz's complaint was received by the Office of the Presidency in  
February and was turned over to the Treasury Secretariat for 
investigation, an office spokeswoman said on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	It would not be the first time the governor has faced  
investigations of his finances. State prosecutors cleared Madrazo 
of charges that he spent ten times more than allowed on his 1994 
governorship campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
