<DOCNO> APW19990306.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 00:23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reid Works To Match Olympic Mates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- David Reid hopes to join Olympic  
teammates Floyd Mayweather and Fernando Vargas as world champions 
tonight when he challenges Laurent Boudouani of France for the WBA 
super welterweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid, the only U.S. boxer to win a gold medal at the 1996 games  
at Atlanta, was a solid favorite in the fight at the Boardwalk 
Convention Center, although he has had only 10 fights to the 
champion's 41. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at the caliber of opposition he's had,'' Al Mitchell,  
Reid's trainer, said of Reid. ``He hasn't been pampered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid (10-0, seven knockouts) has fought two faded former world  
champions (Jorge Vaca and Simon Brown) and several solid 
journeymen. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mayweather, WBC super featherweight champion, and Vargas,  
IBF junior middleweight champion, won world titles quicker than 
Reid, he would become a world champion faster then them in terms of 
number of fights. 
</P>
<P>
	The most dazzling rise from Olympic champion to world champion  
was accomplished by Leon Spinks when he upset Muhammad Ali on a 
split decision in only in his eighth pro fight on Feb. 15, 1978. 
Ali won a rematch on Sept. 15 of that year. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old Boudouani (38-2-1, 32 knockouts) will be making  
the fifth defense of the 154-pound title he won by knocking out 
Julio Vasquez in the fifth round Aug. 21, 1996, in France. 
Tonight's match will be Boudouani's fourth defense and fifth fight 
in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Boudouani's two losses have come inside the scheduled distance.  
He was stopped in the eighth round by Gilbert Baptist in 1991 and 
was knocked out in the eighth round by Bernard Razzano in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's very vulnerable for certain punches,'' said the  
25-year-old Reid, of Philadelphia. ``I'm just going out there and 
use my jab to make openings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight will be preceded on the HBO telecast by a 10-round  
heavyweight bout between Lou Savarese (38-2, 32 knockouts) of New 
York and 6-foot-8 Lance Whitaker (18-0, 18 knockouts) of Van Nuys, 
Calif., who is billed as Mount Whitaker. The telecast will begin at 
10:15 p.m. EST. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 19:42:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft May Fix Privacy Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft will modify its Windows 98 operating  
system to eliminate a problem that could make personal information 
available to hackers or unauthorized persons, The New York Times 
reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said the problem is created by a unique identifying  
number used for registration of Windows programs and other 
Microsoft products that was designed to help Microsoft support 
employees help users diagnose problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The Windows registration number is tied to an individual's name,  
to identifying numbers on the person's computer hardware and to 
documents the user creates. Microsoft said the combination of the 
Windows number with all these data could result in the ability to 
track a single user and the documents the person created across 
vast computer networks, the Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hackers could compromise the resulting database, or subpoenas  
might allow authorities to gain access to information that would 
otherwise remain private and unavailable, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're definitely sensitive to any privacy concerns,'' Robert  
Bennett, Microsoft's group product manager for Windows, told the 
Times. ``The software was not supposed to send this information 
unless the computer user checked a specific option.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts by The Associated Press to reach the Redmond,  
Wash.-based company to confirm that changes would be made were 
unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett said the option to collect the information had been  
added to the software so that Microsoft support employees would be 
able to help users diagnose problems more accurately. He said it 
was never intended to be used for marketing purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett told the Times Microsoft will not only alter the way the  
registration program works in the next maintenance release of 
Windows 98, but technicians would go through the company's data 
bases and expunge information that had been improperly collected as 
a result of earlier versions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said Microsoft has been discussing the issue with a  
Cambridge, Mass., programmer who contacted the company earlier this 
week after discovering that the Microsoft Office business software 
was creating unique numbers identifying a user's personal computer 
and embedding them in spreadsheet and word processing documents. 
</P>
<P>
	The programmer, Robert M. Smith, president of Phar Lap Software  
Inc., told Microsoft he believed the practice created a potential 
threat to privacy, the Times said. Phar Lap is a software tools 
development company. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
