<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ore. MDs Wary of Suicide Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALEM, Ore. (AP) -- Many doctors in Oregon say they will refuse  
to prescribe deadly doses of drugs, frustrating plans of some 
terminally ill patients who want to use the nation's only 
assisted-suicide law. 
</P>
<P>
	Six out of the 15 terminally ill people who used the law to end  
their lives last year were turned down by at least one doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	And by the state's own informal sampling, 67 percent of doctors  
who treat terminally ill patients said they would refuse to 
participate in an assisted suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't been trained to kill people,'' said Portland cancer  
specialist Dr. Jana Reddoch. ``I've been trained to help them live 
as long as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The chief sponsor of the law, Barbara Coombs Lee, said Oregon's  
Death With Dignity Act gives doctors and health care organizations 
the right to ``opt out'' of assisted suicides on moral or ethical 
grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the intention of the law,'' she said. ``It creates a  
right for patients to ask for the prescription but it doesn't 
provide a duty for the physician to provide it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report on last year's experience with assisted suicide,  
conducted by the Oregon Health Division, didn't focus on 
physicians' attitudes on assisted suicide but rather was aimed 
mainly at the characteristics of the terminally ill people who 
requested lethal drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the authors of the report, Dr. Katrina Hedberg, said a  
comprehensive survey now is under way to find out how Oregon 
physicians feel about the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking a look at last year's report, Hedberg guessed that in  
addition to those doctors who refused to take part in suicides on 
moral grounds, others might be worried about being targeted by 
opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is extremely controversial. It's like being an abortion  
doctor,'' she said. ``Doctors who take a stand and participate 
might be subjected to public harassment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some medical observers were surprised by the relatively low  
number of terminally ill people who requested lethal drugs in the 
first full year the law was in effect, and they wonder whether 
physicians' resistance played into that number. 
</P>
<P>
	The Health Division report found that use of the law has so far  
been driven overwhelmingly by the desire of strong-willed patients 
to exercise some control over the way they died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
