<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Dominate Grand Prix Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- Led by rising star Tatiana  
Malinina and world champion Alexei Yagudin, Russian skaters 
dominated Saturday in the finals of the ISU Grand Prix, a tuneup 
before the world championships in Finland later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Malinina, a Russian native now skating for Uzbekistan, upset  
two-time European figure skating champion Maria Butyrskaya, who 
fell twice in a shaky free skate program. 
</P>
<P>
	Yagudin outskated fellow Russians Alexei Urmanov and Evgeny  
Plushenko and American Michael Weiss in a men's competition that 
turned on a battle of the quads -- the quadruple jumps that several 
contenders tried, but none managed to land cleanly. 
</P>
<P>
	Russians failed to win only the pairs competition, which went to  
China's Xue Shen and Hongbo Zhao, who captured the judging with a 
side-by-side triple toe and a triple twist throw. They defeated 
Russian's Olympic silver medalists, Elena Berezhnaya and Anton 
Sikharulidze, after Berezhnaya fell on a triple loop. 
</P>
<P>
	In the ice dance competition, the Russian pair of Anjelika  
Krylov and Oleg Ovsiannikov defeated the French pair of Marina 
Anissina and Gwendal Peizerat. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the attention at the competition was focused on  
Butyrskaya, considered the most likely skater to challenge Michelle 
Kwan at the world championships. But she skated miserably, falling 
first on a triple flip and then spectacularly on a triple salchow, 
skidding across the ice on her stomach toward the judge's stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Her performance was still strong enough to finish second to  
Malinina, who made five clean triple jumps, including an 
outstanding triple lutz, to win the free skating program. Malinina 
also dominated Friday's short program. 
</P>
<P>
	But Malinina, whose strength is technical, not artistic,  
conceded that she was not likely to take on Kwan for the world 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can compete on the technical side,'' she said. ``I won't be  
able to beat her on artistic representation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Irina Slutskaya finished third.  
</P>
<P>
	Russians also swept the top three positions in the men's  
competition, with Yagudin followed by Urmanov and the 16-year-old 
Plushenko. Weiss came in fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	Although none of the top finishers landed a completely clean  
quadruple jump, Yagudin came close, landing on one foot but 
slightly losing his balance. Plushenko attempted two quads -- 
something done only once before in competition -- but didn't land 
either of them cleanly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
