<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard Rescues Three Haitians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Coast Guard rescued three men in the Atlantic  
Ocean off South Florida on Saturday after a boat sank while 
apparently smuggling up to 18 Haitians to the United States. At 
least two bodies were recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard sent ships, helicopters and an airplane to  
search the area between Florida and the Bahamas. 
</P>
<P>
	The survivors said there may have been as many as 18 people on  
the boat, leading the Coast Guard to believe it was a smuggling 
attempt, said Petty Officer Jeff Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally that many people don't get on a boat to cross in the  
middle of the night,'' he said. ``From what we've seen in the past, 
they generally leave from the west end of the Bahamas and come 
across into West Palm Beach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crew of a freighter reported hearing screams from the water  
about 30 miles east of West Palm Beach early Saturday, according to 
a Coast Guard statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Three men were rescued, two of them found clinging to a barrel,  
and were taken to hospitals in Florida. The crew of the Coast Guard 
cutter Matagorda recovered two bodies and saw two other bodies sink 
into the water. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just reiterates the danger that's involved in smuggling  
migrants to the United States,'' said Coast Guard Lt. Ron LaBreck. 
``These people leave in small boats that are generally unseaworthy, 
overcrowded and lacking in even the most basic safety gear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The maximum penalty for people convicted of smuggling refugees  
is life imprisonment and a $250,000 fine, LaBreck said. Refugee 
smuggling that results in death is a capital offense. 
</P>
<P>
	No details were released on the boat that sank.  
</P>
<P>
	The numbers of Cubans and Haitians taking to the sea in efforts  
to reach the United States have increased since 1998, and experts 
expect the trend to continue in 1999. In 1998, Coast Guard vessels 
intercepted 1,025 Cubans and 1,206 Haitians at sea, compared with 
406 Cubans and 587 Haitians in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	On Dec. 17 a 29-foot boat capsized in 6-foot seas off Elliott  
Key, 22 miles south of Miami. Nine drowned and five other 
passengers were lost at sea and presumed dead. Two of the nine 
survivors are accused of being the smugglers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
