<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 16:21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Gives Disaster-Area Refunds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- More than 630,000 taxpayers living in  
federally declared disaster areas are getting a tax refund even if 
they didn't suffer any damage. 
</P>
<P>
	A loophole in the federal tax law has the IRS automatically  
sending refunds for interest charges to taxpayers who lived in an 
area declared a disaster area since 1997 and ended up filing their 
taxes late. 
</P>
<P>
	While the total amount being refunded is unknown, thousands of  
California residents have received refunds, some as much as $4,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm stunned. That is not what Congress intended,'' said Rep.  
Robert Matsui, D-Calif., who serves on the House Ways and Means 
Committee that oversaw the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress had sought to give Americans a break when natural  
disasters make it difficult to file taxes on time, but lawmakers 
apparently had not intended to give every resident of disaster 
areas an interest-free loan on late taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	An IRS spokesman said the agency is simply carrying out the law  
as Congress wrote it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997 and subsequent legislation last  
year gives a tax break to people who lived in counties declared by 
the president to be disaster areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The laws made those residents eligible for refunds of any  
interest they had been charged for paying their taxes late. The 
laws do not require that the taxpayers be affected by the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
