<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 13:22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guillen Still Missing for Pirates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Pirates may find out  
Monday if outfielder Jose Guillen will remain out of spring 
training camp for a few more days -- or, possibly, a few more weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen missed his 11th day of camp Saturday because of an  
immigration dispute resulting from his marriage last fall, a 
ceremony the Pirates apparently did not know about until recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen, the Pirates' right fielder the last two seasons, was  
granted the standard nonimmigrant working visa on Jan. 19, 
permitting him to enter the United States for the baseball season. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen also traveled to Pittsburgh in January to have his  
shoulder examined by team doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	But prior to leaving the Dominican Republic for spring training,  
Guillen attempted to secure a travel visa for his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a statement issued Saturday by the Pirates -- their  
first since Guillen failed to report to camp -- officials of the 
Consular Section determined Guillen violated immigration laws by 
misrepresenting himself on behalf of his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen's working visa then was revoked. Guillen's agent  
subsequently hired an immigration lawyer, and the case is under 
review by the U.S. consulate. A ruling is expected Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not going to let him leave the country until they get  
this cleared up,'' Pirates general manager Cam Bonifay said. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen's absence isn't affecting the Pirates' lineup as manager  
Gene Lamont plays mostly farmhands early in the spring training 
schedule. But Guillen is missing valuable training time, a bigger 
factor than normal because he played only a few games in winter 
ball. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0043 </DOCNO>
