<DOCNO> APW19990306.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 10:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Austrian Wins Women Skiing Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. MORITZ, Switzerland (AP) -- Austrian Alexandra Meissnitzer  
captured the women's overall World Cup title today with a 
fourth-place finish in the super-G race. 
</P>
<P>
	Michaela Dorfmeister, another Austrian, won the race and kept  
alive her chances for the super-G season title. Dorfmeister was 
timed in 1:29.17. 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Renate Goetschl finished in 1:29.37, beating out  
American Kathleen Monahan, who was clocked in 1:29.57. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Monahan's first career trip to the podium. Monahan's  
previous-best result was an eighth place in the super-G in Mommoth 
Mountain earlier this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really surprised but it's dawning on me more and more,''  
said Monahan, who was the first skier out of the start hut. 
``Because I was first I didn't know what to expect so I tried for 
an aggressive line. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I saw Meissnitzer's time was slower than mine I knew I'd  
had an awesome run, because she's been skiing really fast,'' added 
Monahan, who joined the World Cup circuit in 1992. ``This is really 
good for the upcoming finals in Sierra Nevada, because it gives me 
a lot of confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Meissnitzer's fourth place finish was enough to get her  
the overall championship, it was not quite enough to wrap up the 
disipline title. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorfmeister advanced to second place in the super-G standings,  
and had an outside shot at the title going into the World Cup final 
next week. She has to win in Spain to capture the discipline 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory today was was Dorfmeister's first ever in the  
super-G, and only her second win ever. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
