<DOCNO> APW19990306.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 13:42:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire Doesn't Homer in 1999 Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- Maybe hitting 70 homers again won't be so  
easy for Mark McGwire. 
</P>
<P>
	Big Mac looked like a regular ballplayer preparing for the  
season, not baseball's new single-season home run king, as he made 
his 1999 debut Saturday against the Montreal Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, whose 450-foot home runs in last year's spring opener  
set off his record-setting spree of 70 homers, flied out to center 
and was hit by a pitch in his two plate appearances in the St. 
Louis Cardinals' 4-3 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just wanted the get him two at-bats,'' Cardinals manager  
Tony La Russa said. ``It's early in the spring. He still has time 
to loosen up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire received a standing ovation before his first at-bat as  
the 6,938 fans thanked him for the glorious run he took the sport 
on last year and urged an encore in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Thurman, who allowed No. 69 on the last day of the 1998  
season, didn't give up No. 1 this season. Instead, he got McGwire 
to fly out to Rondell White on a 2-2 pitch for the second out of 
the first inning. 
</P>
<P>
	In his second at-bat, McGwire was hit on his left elbow pad by a  
Mike Johnson fastball, drawing scattered boos from the crowd. 
McGwire calmly jogged to first, where he was stranded. 
</P>
<P>
	``My heart skips a beat whenever one of my players is hit,'' La  
Russa said, pretending McGwire is no different than the other 59 
players in camp. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire was replaced by Chris Haas after the third inning and  
didn't talk after the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans did see one long ball, when Cardinals phenom J.D. Drew hit  
a two-run homer in the third off Johnson for St. Louis' first two 
runs. Drew finished 2-for-3 with a stolen base and was hit by a 
pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The Expos may have been the home team at Roger Dean Stadium,  
which they share with the Cardinals, but they couldn't have felt 
like it. There was only a smattering of Expos blue in the 
Cardinal-red sea of St. Louis hats and McGwire shirts in the 
stands. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans lined up more than five hours before first pitch for a  
chance at the 200 standing room only tickets to the sold out game, 
and those lucky enough to have a ticket were frustrated to find out 
only Expos programs would be on sale -- a cover photo of Valdimir 
Guerrero doesn't have the same allure as Big Mac. 
</P>
<P>
	As has become customary everywhere McGwire goes, fans arrived  
early to see one of baseball's best shows, McGwire taking batting 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of fans with cameras clicking gathered near the slugger  
as he hit soft tosses into a screen behind home plate while his 
teammates hit live pitching. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's an electricity here,'' said St. Louis' Carlos Baerga,  
who is spending his first spring with baseball's biggest attraction 
after nine seasons with the Indians and Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes later, McGwire took his first turn in the cage and  
bunted twice, much to the disappointment to the fans. He then hit 
four home runs in eight swings, including two that easily cleared 
the Expos' offices more than 50 feet behind the left-field fence. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was here last year for batting practice, I was almost  
alone,'' Cardinals fan Rob Biondolino said. ``Now there are 
thousands of fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the stadium, Cletus Boyer -- no relation to the former  
Yankees third baseman of the same name or his brother Ken of the 
Cardinals -- was selling copies of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch's 
coverage of McGwire's record 62nd homer for $15. 
</P>
<P>
	If the fans have their way, that will soon be old news.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's no reason why he can't break the record again,''  
Biondolino said. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Derrick May's RBI single off Mike Busby capped a two-run  
ninth inning rally for Montreal. ... Keith Evans picked up the win, 
allowing one run in the ninth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
