<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dole Expects Kosovo Deal Sunday  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Former Sen. Bob Dole said today ethnic Albanians  
had promised to sign a Kosovo peace plan tomorrow that would give 
them autonomy -- and the breakthrough puts pressure on the Serbs to 
accept the deal or face NATO airstrikes. Dole delivered the news to 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright after traveling to the 
region, at President Clinton's request, to meet with Kosovo's 
ethnic Albanians. The mission is intended to reach agreement before 
a new round of peace talks March 15. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes Senate on Education  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton pressured Senate GOP leaders  
today to allow a vote on a measure subsidizing the hiring of more 
teachers and aimed at reducing class size in America's schools. 
``The choice is simple: Are we going to give Americans smaller 
classes, or more partisanship?'' Clinton said in his weekly radio 
address. Clinton was addressing Republican objections to an 
amendment to the GOP-written ``ed-flex'' bill, which would give 
state and local officials more leeway in how they spend federal 
education funds. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Jets Bomb Iraqi Sites  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- U.S. Air Force jets today bombed five  
Iraqi anti-aircraft sites after being fired upon during a patrol 
over northern Iraq, U.S. military officials said. The Iraqi sites 
were south of the Saddam Lake near the city of Mosul, 250 miles 
north of Baghdad, said a statement from Operation Northern Watch, 
which enforces the northern no-fly zone. U.S. jets have been 
striking Iraqi military sites on an almost daily basis since late 
December in response to Iraq firing at the planes or locking its 
radar systems on to them. 

</P>
<P>
	Khmer Rouge Chief Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- Cambodian soldiers arrested the last  
senior leader of the murderous Khmer Rouge guerrilla army today 
near the northern border with Thailand, senior generals said. Known 
as ``The Butcher'' because of his legendary brutality, Ta Mok was 
captured alone and flown by helicopter to Phnom Penh for trial, 
Defense Minister Tea Banh said. The one-legged guerrilla army chief 
was the last senior leader of the brutal 1975-79 Khmer Rouge regime 
at large. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: China Stole U.S. Nuclear Secrets  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- China reportedly stole secrets from an American  
government lab, and used the information to help increase its 
nuclear capabilities. Today's New York Times reports that China's 
technological advance was gained from the mid-1980s theft of U.S. 
nuclear secrets from the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New 
Mexico, according to administration officials. The espionage was 
not detected until 1995, when American experts analyzing Chinese 
nuclear test results found similarities to America's most advanced 
miniature warhead, the W-88, The Times reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. Bush Had Death Threat  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Federal agents failed to tell the security staff  
for Gov. George W. Bush about a plot by a group of militant 
separatists to kill him two years ago, The Dallas Morning News 
reported today. An FBI informant who infiltrated the antigovernment 
Republic of Texas said he told the agents about two meetings when 
assassination was discussed. Dudley M. Thomas, director of the 
state agency that protects the governor, said his officers should 
have known about the threats. But FBI agents said they didn't 
confide in the agency because the threats were not considered 
credible. 

</P>
<P>
	Aspirin Centennial Celebrated  
</P>
<P>
	LEVERKUSEN, Germany (AP) -- Bayer AG celebrated the 100th  
anniversary of its wonder drug -- aspirin -- today by turning its 
company headquarters into the world's largest pillbox. Using 
242,190 square feet of cloth, hung from scaffolding by 50 mountain 
climbers, Bayer turned the 400-foot tall building into a giant 
Bayer aspirin carton. On Aug. 10, 1897, a young Bayer researcher, 
Felix Hoffman, first synthesized acetylsalicylic acid, aspirin's 
active ingredient. The celebration marked the 100th anniversary of 
the day the name ``aspirin'' was first registered as a trademark. 

</P>
<P>
	IOC Eyes Reform Commission  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee is backing off  
a plan to strip rank-and-file members of voting for Olympic cities. 
IOC leaders told The Associated Press yesterday that a reform 
commission will be proposed at the special general assembly March 
17-18 in Lausanne, Switzerland. The panel will consider ways of 
changing the structure and operations of the IOC, setting the stage 
for what could be the biggest changes in the body's 105 years. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
