<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 10:26:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Debate Reichstag Naming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- The old Reichstag building in Berlin should keep  
its name when it becomes the seat of parliament again next month, 
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder was quoted Saturday as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The neo-Renaissance stone edifice has been known as the  
Reichstag since its completion in 1894. But some lawmakers, 
including the parliamentary president, feel that the name -- Reich 
means empire in German -- has too many negative historical 
connotations. 
</P>
<P>
	To many, it conjures images of Prussian militarism and they want  
it changed before the key is handed over April 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder, however, was quoted by the Frankfurter Allgemeine  
Zeitung newspaper as saying everyone knows the historic structure 
as the Reichstag and he saw no reason to change the name. The 
Germans are ``too uptight'' in dealing with their history, he 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper quoted him as saying his Social Democratic Party had  
an ``old bad habit'' of trying to tell people how to behave, and 
calling the Reichstag something neutral like Assembly Hall, one of 
the proposals, would be ``absurd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parliamentary president Wolfgang Thierse had called for renaming  
the building, which is nearing the end of massive renovations. He 
said the name ``Reichstag'' no longer fits with Germany's postwar 
democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Parliament's council of elders put off a decision on Thursday,  
but agreed that signs pointing to the building, nearing the end of 
renovations, and a planned subway stop would refer to the Deutscher 
Bundestag, the name of the postwar German parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
