<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Tries To Save Spinning Craft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ground controllers worked Saturday to develop  
a method of regaining control of a science satellite that was 
spinning uselessly in orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wide-Field Infrared Explorer, or Wire, has been spinning at  
one revolution per second since its launch Thursday night, 
apparently because of the thruster-like action of hydrogen gas 
venting from a system used to keep the satellite's telescope 
extremely cold. 
</P>
<P>
	The $67 million mission was designed to help scientists  
understand how and when galaxies formed, and the history of star 
formation. 
</P>
<P>
	Ground controllers were in contact with the spacecraft and were  
trying to write a software program that would use the spacecraft's 
limited attitude control system to make it stop spinning. 
</P>
<P>
	``The subsystems are in good shape,'' said Jim Watzin, a project  
manager in NASA's Small Explorer program. ``The solar arrays are 
generating power and the battery is fully charged. We have plenty 
of power to effect a recovery.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 05:22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Few States Gain Ground in Reading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Connecticut led the nation in the latest  
national reading test scores for fourth- and eighth-graders. 
</P>
<P>
	The state-by-state results were released Friday by the  
Department of Education. The test, the National Assessment of 
Educational Progress, was given by 39 states last year. These 
results measure about 18,680 fourth and eighth graders. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut had the nation's highest student scores as  
determined by the National Assessment Governing Board, which sets 
the test standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The breakdown of state-by-state test results date back to 1992.  
</P>
<P>
	The national results of the 1998 reading tests, released last  
month, showed improvements in each of the three tested grade levels 
-- fourth, eighth and 12th -- from the 1994 tests. Eighth graders 
improved from 1992. Public and private school students were tested. 
</P>
<P>
	The state results, which exclude private school students and  
12th graders, showed average reading scores increased significantly 
in nine states, and there were no significant declines. 
</P>
<P>
	For fourth-graders, Connecticut's students scored highest. The  
next highest, in alphabetical order, include Colorado, Iowa, 
Kansas, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Montana, New Hampshire and 
Wisconsin, as well as the Department of Defense overseas schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut also scored highest among eighth-graders. Coming  
next, in alphabetical order, were Kansas, Maine, Massachusetts, 
Minnesota, Montana, New York, Oklahoma, Oregon, Utah, Virginia, 
Washington, Wisconsin, Washington and Department of Defense 
overseas and domestic schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Between 1992 and 1998, Connecticut, Colorado, Kentucky,  
Mississippi, North Carolina and the Virgin Islands all showed 
gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite progress, gains in reading haven't been as widespread or  
consistent as those in math, said Wilmer S. Cody, the Kentucky 
education commissioner and a member of the testing board. Also, 
there are still wide gaps in achievement by race, gender and 
poverty level, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	States that did not participate were Alaska, Idaho, Illinois,  
Indiana, Nebraska, New Jersey, North Dakota, Ohio, Pennsylvania, 
South Dakota and Vermont. 
</P>
<P>
	Individual state scores are available on the Internet, at the  
Education Department Web site, http://nces.ed.gov 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 18:22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reid Wins 400m at NCAA Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Suziann Reid of Texas extended her streak of  
collegiate victories at 400 meters Saturday by successfully 
defending her title in the event and then ran a strong anchor in 
the 1,600-meter relay as Texas retained the NCAA Indoors Track and 
Field championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid got out first in the 400, completing her first lap in a  
speedy 24.29 seconds. She pulled away from Baylor's Yulana Nelson 
down the backstretch to win the event for a 10th consecutive time 
in 51.68, nearly a second faster than her winning time last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas senior came up short in a bid to improve on the meet  
record of 51.05 set by Maicel Malone of Arizona State in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping to get the record, but it's fine,'' said Reid,  
whose time was the fastest by a woman in collegiate competition 
this season. ``I did my job. I'm here to make points for my team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She helped do that again in the final event, which began with  
the Lady Longhorns tied for the team lead with LSU. Texas moved to 
the front about halfway through the relay and was still there when 
Reid got the baton. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Reid on the winning team was Angel Patterson, Aminah  
Haddad and Tanya Jarrett. The quartet combined to cover the 
distance in 3:31.55, the second-fastest women's collegiate time 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid had special motivation as she ran at the RCA Dome with  
members of her family in the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``They came all the way from Maryland. I had to put on a show,''  
she said. ``I felt comfortable, confident and relaxed. My top goal 
was to defend my title in my last indoor champions and I was really 
happy to be able to do it in front of my parents who drove 14 hours 
just to watch me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas finished with 61 points and LSU, which had its streak of  
five straight championships snapped by the Lady Longhorns last 
year, was second with 57 and Southern Methoidist was third with 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas used depth to win its 15th men's indoor title in 16  
years. The Razorbacks accumulated 65 points although their only 
victory came in the triple jump -- an event they've dominated. 
Melvin Lister went 55-0 3/4 as a Razorback won the event for the 12th 
time in 17 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford was runner-up for the second straight year with 42 1/2  
points and South Carolina placed third with 27. 
</P>
<P>
	The men's meet produced the only collegiate record when Jacob  
Davis of Texas cleared 19-2 1/2 in the pole vault, topping the 
collegiate and meet record of 19-1 1/2 set in 1994 by Lawrence Johnson 
of Tennessee 
</P>
<P>
	LSU's bid suffered a serious blow with Peta-Gaye Dowdie, the 200  
champion on Friday and the fastest qualifier for the finals of the 
60 was disqualified for a false start. Debbie Ferguson of Georgia, 
the runner-up in 1998, won the event in 7:24 and LaKeisha Backus of 
Texas, who placed seventh in defense of her 1998 championship in 
the 200 on Friday, was third. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida's Hazel Clark successfully defended her championship in  
the 800, covering the distance in a meet record 2:01.77. Amy Wickus 
of Wisconsin set the former mark of 2:02.05 in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming out quickly, Clark completed the first 200 in 29.1 and  
was never seriously challenged. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stayed away from track for a long time because I wasn't sure  
I could live up to expectations,'' said Clark, who now plans to 
compete professionally. ``I'm sad to be leaving this (college), but 
I'm very excited about the next stage of my life. I'm going to try 
to get some sponsorships and we'll see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another defending champion, Pittsburgh's Trecia Smith, finished  
second in the triple jump. North Carolina's Nicole Gamble soared 
46-1 1/4 to win the event, while Smith's best effort was 46 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Other women's champions determined Saturday included freshman  
Kate Vermoulen of West Virginia, 4:39.07 in the mile; Villanova's 
Carrie Tollefson, 9:15.05 in the 3,000; and Erin Aldrich of Texas, 
6-3 1/2 in the high jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri's Derrick Peterson flirted with the meet record in the  
men's 800 after placing second in the event last year. Peterson won 
the event this year in 1:45.88, just a fraction of a second off the 
record mark of 1:45.80 set by Einars Tupuritis of Wichita State in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Two freshmen left the RCA Dome with collegiate titles. Clemson's  
Ato Modibo won the men's 400 in 46.11 and Tennessee's Leonard Scott 
took top honors in the 60-meter dash in 6.58.46 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Washington State's Bernard Lagat became the first  
men's competitor to finish first in both the mile and 3,000 on 
Saturday since Joe Falcon of Arkansas completed the feat in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Abilene Christian successfully defended its  
championships in the men's and women's competition for Division II 
schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
