<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dole Advances Kosovo Peace Deal  
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanian leaders could sign a  
peace agreement for Kosovo province within days, Bob Dole declared 
yesterday. Dole, a longtime supporter of the Albanian push for 
self-rule in Kosovo, came to the region to urge ethnic Albanians to 
approve the deal immediately. ``This agreement could be signed 
within 48 hours,'' said Dole, who was sent to the region at 
President Clinton's request. 

</P>
<P>
	China Said To Steal Nuclear Secrets  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- China reportedly stole secrets from an American  
government lab, and used the information to help increase its 
nuclear capabilities. Today's New York Times reports that China's 
technological advance was gained from the mid-1980s theft of U.S. 
nuclear secrets from the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New 
Mexico, according to administration officials. The act of espionage 
was not detected until 1995, when American experts analyzing 
Chinese nuclear test results found similarities to America's most 
advanced miniature warhead, the W-88, The Times reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Applications Rise at Colleges  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Growing Internet use combined with a surge in high  
school graduates helped boost the number of college applications 
submitted last year, several school officials have reported. 
Although most colleges don't accept applications via the Internet, 
it's becoming far more common for them to post blank applications 
on the Web, allowing would-be students to download forms and mail 
them in later. Even without the Internet, schools would probably be 
reporting a jump in applicants. The number of high school seniors 
has been increasing about 3 percent annually in recent years. 
Experts predict there will be close to 3 million high school 
graduates next year, up from 2.6 million in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the number of applications is outstripping the increase  
in students. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Accuse Wal-Mart of Bias  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The federal government has sued  
Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, accusing it of using job 
questionnaires to screen out disabled applicants. The suit claims 
Wal-Mart violated the Americans with Disabilities Act, attorneys 
for the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission said 
yesterday. The questionnaire asked applicants to indicate if they 
might need any accommodation to perform required duties. The EEOC 
says it is illegal to ask about disability before a job offer is 
made. 

</P>
<P>
	Administration To Attack Net Fraud  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Portraying the Internet as a growing  
playground for criminals, the chief of the Justice Department's 
criminal division said yesterday the Clinton administration is 
readying a new program to curb fraud on the Web. Stock trading by 
computer, online auctions and direct sales of products to 
businesses and consumers already account for billions of dollars in 
sales each year. The new program, being developed under Vice 
President Al Gore, will ``represent the first time the department 
has made Internet fraud a priority,'' said Assistant Attorney 
General James K. Robinson. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Hits Record High  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average soared 268.68  
points to a new record yesterday. The Dow cracked through 9,700 for 
the first time to finish at 9,736.08, topping its Jan. 8 record 
finish of 9,643.32 and bringing 1999's rise to 6 percent. Stocks 
were ignited by a government employment report that calmed worries 
about rising interest rates. 

</P>
<P>
	Controversy at World Pole Vault  
</P>
<P>
	MAEBASHI, Japan (AP) -- The pole vault competition at the World  
Indoor Track and Field Championships was held up for 10 minutes 
today while officials tried to decide whether French vaulter Jean 
Galfione touched the bar with his hands on what turned out to be 
the winning jump of 6.00 meters (19 feet, 8 1/4 inches). The jump was 
at first disallowed by technical delegate Cecil Smith of Canada. 
But that decision was overruled and Galfione, the 1996 Olympic 
champion, was declared the winner. 

</P>
<P>
	Tyson Won't Face More Jail in Ind.  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Former heavyweight champion Mike Tyson can  
look forward to restarting his boxing career now that his legal 
problems are resolved. Tyson must serve an extra 60 days in a 
Maryland jail for violating his Indiana probation for a 1992 rape 
conviction, under an agreement filed yesterday in Marion County 
(Ind.) Superior Court. But when Tyson will actually be released 
from jail and resume his career is unclear. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
