<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UConn's Freeman Named Tourney MVP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On a team with as many weapons as Big East  
champion Connecticut, Kevin Freeman often gets overlooked, hidden 
behind teammates like Richard Hamilton, the conference's co-Player 
of the Year, and point guard Khalid El-Amin. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe that's why when it came time to pick this season's  
all-conference team, Freeman was missing in action. 
</P>
<P>
	Not on the first team.  
</P>
<P>
	Not on the second team.  
</P>
<P>
	Not on the third team.  
</P>
<P>
	Not a problem.  
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-7 junior from Springfield, Mass., made up for the  
snub by winning the Most Outstanding Player award Saturday night as 
the Huskies captured the conference tournament for the second 
straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not making one of the teams really hurt,'' Freeman said.  
``This is probably the best thing that can happen without having 
them vote over again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman had a modest nine points and six rebounds in the 82-63  
destruction of St. John's but was a major part of the defensive 
effort that turned the game into a blowout early. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a role change for him after he had been the difference on  
offense for the Huskies in their first two tournament wins, scoring 
22 against Seton Hall and 21 against Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I played like that most of the year,'' Freeman said. ``I do  
what the team needs me to do to help us win. Today was defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman had plenty of credentials for all-conference honors. He  
was UConn's No. 3 scorer with 12.8 points per game and leading 
rebounder with 208 for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	He is No. 2 in career field goal percentage for the Huskies at  
56 percent and led the team with a 60.7 percentage this season. 
During the Big East tournament, he passed the 1,000-point plateau, 
becoming only the fourth player in UConn basketball history with at 
least 1,000 points and 600 rebounds before the conclusion of his 
junior season. 
</P>
<P>
	All of this is often hidden by the flash and dash of Hamilton  
and El-Amin. Those two took care of the offense against St. John's 
but Freeman wasn't overlooked this time. 
</P>
<P>
	When he stepped to the foul line with just over 10 minutes to  
play and the issue well in hand, the sellout Madison Square Garden 
crowd of 19,548 expressed its appreciation, chanting ``MVP! MVP! 
MVP!'' Freeman responded with a huge grin. Somebody had noticed. 
</P>
<P>
	It was payback for the earlier snub.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was surprised at that,'' he said of the all-conference vote.  
``I did a good job. I thought I was at least third team. I play 
hard. You should be recognized for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's not a problem within his team.  
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jim Calhoun has been touting Freeman for some time.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think Kevin had nothing more remarkable than in the sense  
that he showed more of what he is.'' he said. ``We see this every 
day in practice. He ignited us to where we are tonight. He was one 
of the major, major reasons we came into this tournament at 25-2.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And he's a major reason why they leave it 28-2.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
