<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Meissnitzer Eyes 2 World Cup Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. MORITZ, Switzerland (AP) -- Renate Goetschl has already  
wrapped up the World Cup downhill title, and Austria could load up 
on two more crystal globes before the weekend is out if Alexandra 
Meissnitzer has her way. 
</P>
<P>
	A double gold medalist at the World Championships in Vail last  
month, Meissnitzer now has her sights set firmly on two World Cup 
crowns. 
</P>
<P>
	All she needs is a win in today's Super-G -- a specialty of  
Meissnitzer's -- and the 25-year-old Austrian would own both the 
overall and Super-G crowns when she leaves St. Moritz for the World 
Cup finals in Sierra Nevada, Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	Though her sixth-place tie with Hilde Gerg in Friday's downhill  
did not allow her to clinch the overall -- Gerg is the only skier 
who can mathematically still overtake her -- Meissnitzer only needs 
to score two more points than Gerg in today's super-G to clinch the 
overall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still 100 percent motivated because there is still so much  
at stake,'' said Meissnitzer, who won gold in the super-G and giant 
slalom at the worlds. ``I hope I can win the titles, but in Sierra 
Nevada there will still be the giant slalom to be decided.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With super-G specialists Martina Ertl of Germany and France's  
Regine Cavagnoud both sidelined with knee injuries, Meissnitzer has 
received help from two of her other main challengers. 
</P>
<P>
	With 1,490 points, Meissnitzer holds a 399-point advantage over  
Gerg in the overall rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	If Gerg can finish ahead of Meissnitzer, the German would  
virtually still have to sweep all four races at the finals if she 
wants to overtake her Austrian rival. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a tall order for the German, who saw her chances at the  
downhill title evaporate Friday when Goetschl rocketed to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Goetschl, meanwhile, can rest easy, having already claimed the  
only title she is realistically in contention for. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so happy to have clinched the title here so I can go to  
the finals, relax and enjoy everything Sierra Nevada has to 
offer,'' said Goetschl, the World Cup downhill titlist in 1997 and 
runnerup behind Germany's Katja Seizinger last year. ``I'm so happy 
I was so consistent this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't explain how I did so well,'' added Goetschl, who won  
four World Cup downhill races in addition to her victory at the 
worlds. ``I just think everything came together at the same time. I 
have good equipment, great physical and mental form.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since joining the World Cup circuit in 1993 Goetschl had one  
victory each year until this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
