<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oregon Wreck Becomes Tourist Stop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALDPORT, Ore. (AP) -- While the wreck of the New Carissa is an  
environmental time bomb to some, its rusty hulk means profits to 
savvy entrepreneurs cashing in on a wave of gawkers here to have a 
look. 
</P>
<P>
	Only hours after the ship's oil-laden, broken bow nosed onto the  
beach, T-shirts began appearing emblazoned with the words: ``The 
New Carissa Tour '99 -- Floating to a coastal town near you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going like crazy. We can't keep them in,'' Cherie  
Turner, a clerk at a local drug store, said Friday. ``Visitors are 
buying them and so are local people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``No vacancy'' signs glowed at many motels where two or three  
guests on another winter weekday would be a welcome event. 
</P>
<P>
	So many sightseers have flooded this town of 1,750 to catch a  
glimpse of the wreck that Gov. John Kitzhaber declared a local 
state of emergency and warned people to stay away. 
</P>
<P>
	Against this backdrop, workers on the beach unfurled a new,  
9-ton 14-inch-thick, polyester tow rope that will be used to haul 
away the wreck. Salvage crews hope to connect the rope today. 
</P>
<P>
	The bow is still believed to be holding up to 130,000 gallons of  
fuel oil, apparently the source of tar balls clinging to 23 miles 
of beach. Already, wildlife officials have counted 242 dead birds, 
105 of which were oiled. Another 116 shore birds are still in 
rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans call for towing the hulk more than 200 miles out to sea  
and sinking it. Salvage experts say water pressure and the 
34-degree temperature on the ocean floor will solidify the oil and 
prevent it from becoming an environmental hazard. 
</P>
<P>
	Ever since the ship ran aground down the coast at Coos Bay on  
Feb. 4, Coast Guard and salvage crews have faced one setback after 
another. 
</P>
<P>
	The ship was set afire, which succeeded in burning away half the  
oil on board. But it broke in two and spilled 70,000 gallons. 
</P>
<P>
	The first attempt to bury the bow at sea failed earlier this  
week when the tow line ripped loose. The carcass of the ship ended 
up here, 80 miles north of its last stop along the coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
