<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Appointment of Robertson Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- The appointment of Pat Robertson to an  
economic development panel is being criticized by people who point 
out that one of the religious broadcaster's charitable enterprises 
is being investigated for alleged unethical business practices. 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Janet D. Howell, whose complaint two years ago set  
off the probe, said Robertson's ``ethics are under serious 
question, and that's not the kind of image that should be put forth 
by Virginia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations relate to Operation Blessing, a food and medical  
relief organization that provides flights around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	As a charity, the organization gets a sales tax exemption. But  
Howell challenged the exemption after two Operation Blessing pilots 
complained that some of their planes were used almost exclusively 
to ferry equipment to a Robertson-owned diamond mine in Congo. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Miner, a spokesman for Gov. Jim Gilmore, defended  
Robertson's appointment to the Virginia Economic Development 
Partnership, saying no wrongdoing has been proven. 
</P>
<P>
	A Robertson spokeswoman, Patty Silverman, said ``we're very  
confident that the outcome will be resolved'' favorably to 
Operation Blessing, which she said has provided $96 million in 
relief to 130 million people since 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
