<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smoke Forces 2 Jets To Land Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- Smoke in the cabin forced a Boeing 757  
with at least 150 people on board to make an emergency landing 
Saturday at Greenville-Spartanburg International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	And in Cleveland, a Continental Express plane returned after  
takeoff when smoke appeared in the cockpit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boeing was traveling from Atlanta to Washington, D.C., when  
the pilot reported oil-pressure problems and landed in South 
Carolina shortly after 11 a.m., Airport Operations Supervisor Fred 
Bright said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured and the plane was grounded for repairs.  
</P>
<P>
	WSPA-TV reported the plane was a Delta Air Lines flight. Calls  
to Delta's headquarters in Atlanta were not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The Continental Express was headed to Minneapolis on Saturday  
with 40 passengers when it landed at about 6:30 p.m. at Cleveland 
Hopkins International Airport. The plane taxied to a gate without 
evacuations. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the smoke was de-icing fluid getting in the air  
conditioning system, officials said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
