<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 00:51:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Controversy at Pole Vault Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAEBASHI, Japan (AP) -- It's a rule American pole vaulter Jeff  
Hartwig has always believed should be stricken from the books. Now 
he has even better reason to oppose it. 
</P>
<P>
	The pole vault competition at the World Indoor Track and Field  
Championships was held up for 10 minutes today while officials 
tried to decide whether French vaulter Jean Galfione touched the 
bar with his hands on what turned out to be the winning jump of 
6.00 meters (19 feet, 8 1/4 inches). 
</P>
<P>
	The jump was at first disallowed by technical delegate Cecil  
Smith of Canada. But that decision was overruled and Galfione, the 
1996 Olympic champion, was declared the winner. He is only the 
fourth person ever to clear 6.00 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the rule, a vault is only a foul if the athlete  
deliberately replaces a bar about to fall from the supports with 
his hands or fingers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig finished with 19-6 1/4, an American record.  
</P>
<P>
	``I tried not to touch the bar, but I probably did. I didn't put  
it back,'' Galfione said. ``But it's finished. This law is stupid. 
I feel sorry for Jeff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Had Hartwig won, it would have been the first major pole vault  
title for the United States in 31 years. He said he was happy with 
the American record, but felt the controversy stopped him from 
going higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I'm disappointed about is that they held the competition  
up for 10 minutes while they discussed it,'' he said. ``That killed 
everything. Ignorance on the part of the officials killed it for 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team appealed the ruling, but the appeal failed.  
</P>
<P>
	Craig Masbach, chief executive of U.S. Track and Field, said the  
ruling was a ``mockery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They admit he touched it, but they didn't feel he replaced it.  
They've made a mockery of the rule,'' he said. ``Either get rid of 
the rule and I'll accept the decision, or enforce the rule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today's competition held few other surprises -- but some very  
good performances. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them was by Frankie Fredericks of Namibia, winner of four  
Olympic silver medals, who finally came up gold. 
</P>
<P>
	He won the 200 in meet-record time 20.10 seconds, the  
second-fastest time in history. Obadele Thompson of Barbados became 
the No. 3 career performer, finishing second at 20.26. Kevin Little 
of the United States won his third bronze in the event, placing 
third at 20.42. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to add as many titles to my name as I can,''  
Fredericks said. ``And it's not a silver this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Romania's Gabriela Szabo, the 1997 women's 3,000 champion, won  
the 1,500 in 4:03.23, a meet record and the fastest time in the 
world this year. She is going for a distance double in the 3,000 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to think about the 3,000 yet,'' she said. ``I'm  
just so happy to have won today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haile Gebrselassie, who is already halfway to an unprecedented  
double in the men's distance events, advanced to Sunday's 
1,500-meter final by winning his semifinal heat in 3:41.21 -- the 
fastest of the two heats. 
</P>
<P>
	Gebrselassie won his second straight 3,000-meter title Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Ionela Tirlea of Romania won the women's 200 in 22.39, the best  
in the world this year; Tatyana Kotova of Russia took the women's 
long jump at 22-6, and Vita Pavlysh of Ukraine successfully 
defended her title in the women's shot put at 70-3 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Mozambique's Maria Mutola, seeking to become the first woman to  
win four track gold medals at the championships, cruised into the 
women's 800-meter final with an easy victory at 2:02.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutola is the 1993, 1995 and 1997. Only Bulgarian high jumper  
Stefka Kostadinova, with five titles, has won more world indoor 
titles than Mutola. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutola is unbeaten this season in six races, including a world  
record at 1,000 meters, and is the prohibitive favorite in Sunday's 
final. 
</P>
<P>
	American Jearl Miles-Clark, the defending champion in the  
women's 400, had the world's fastest time, 50.83, in winning her 
semifinal heat and leading the way into Sunday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Her performance came shortly after Germany's Grit Breuer, the  
European indoor and outdoor champion, won the other heat in 50.88, 
also under the previous 1999 world best of 50.91. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark's Wilson Kipketer, who seemed invincible at the 1997  
championships, breaking the world 800-meter record twice, finished 
second to South Africa's Johan Botha in a semifinal heat, 1:46.65 
to 1:46.76. Germany's Nico Motchebon (1:47.05) and Hungary's Balazs 
Koranyi (1:48.74) won the other heats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
