<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IUP Moves To Change Indian Mascot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PUNXSUTAWNEY, Pa. (AP) -- The trustees at Indiana University of  
Pennsylvania have voted to change the school's mascot from an 
Indian to a bear, although the team's nickname will remain the 
Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	The unanimous vote on Friday at the school's satellite campus in  
Punxsutawney, 64 miles northeast of Pittsburgh, follows the 
recommendation made by a school panel on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	University president Lawrence Pettit recommended changing the  
mascot to improve the school's image and allow it to use the new 
mascot as a marketing tool. The university stopped using the Indian 
mascot and Indian-head logo in 1991, instead using the campus bell 
tower or the letter ``I'' as a symbol. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been without a mascot for nine years, and we were  
feeling a little lost,'' university spokeswoman Michelle Fryling 
said. ``We want to maintain the respect and recognition of the 
Native American culture, and we know that the bear will not be used 
in a demeaning way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pettit said the nickname ``Indians'' should stay because many  
rivers and counties carry Indian names. The panel recommended that 
a bear be used as a mascot because it is native to the region and 
revered by many tribes. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the committee and Pettit consulted Indian advocacy groups  
about the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the name `Indians' that people find objectionable,''  
Fryling said. ``It's when you try to have a stereotypical Indian in 
headdress and war paint that it is objectionable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the leader of one national Indian advocacy group found the  
compromise ``silly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a small step in the right direction, but it's a foolish  
compromise,'' said Suzan Shown Harjo, president of The Morning Star 
Institute in Washington. ``It would be like a school team name 
called the Whites or the Blacks, and the mascot is a monkey. I 
mean, what is the thinking here?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, Harjo filed a lawsuit seeking to force the NFL's  
Washington Redskins to change their nickname. A decision is still 
pending. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think people lose their sense of subtlety and discernment  
when it comes to native people,'' she said. ``I don't know how many 
times we can say this, that we're people, not mascots, and we're 
human beings, and we do not want to be used for America's 
recreation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fryling said the university has not yet chosen a design for its  
new mascot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have the bear yet,'' she said. ``We don't know what  
we're going to do, but we know we can have a lot of fun with it, 
and we know that we can maintain the respect for the bear as a 
Native American symbol.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
