<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thorn Apple Files for Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) -- The meat producer Thorn Apple Valley  
Inc. has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection after losing 
millions of dollars in a huge meat recall and the Russian economic 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Company President Joel Dorfman said an investment banking firm  
was looking for new investors, or possibly a buyer, for the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The firm reported a $12 million loss for its second fiscal  
quarter, ending in December. And it may lose $5 million to $6 
million more this quarter from the recall of 30 million pounds of 
meat from its Forest City, Ark., plant, where meat samples tested 
positive for harmful bacteria. 
</P>
<P>
	The Southfield-based meat producer will continue to operate its  
plants in Michigan, North Carolina, Arkansas and Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorfman said Thorn Apple Valley was recovering from the loss of  
sales from Russia when the meat recall hit Jan. 22. When the 
Russian currency collapsed, Thorn Apple Valley was left without a 
customer for 1.5 million hot dogs. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
