<DOCNO> APW19990306.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 10:12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Working Helps Wilson, Hanks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- When Rita Wilson started reading the script  
for a TV movie, ``Invisible Child,'' she feared it would be another 
``nanny-from-hell story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It turned out to be very different. In the Lifetime channel  
movie showing Monday, March 8 at 9 p.m., Tushka Bergen portrays a 
perfectly kind and efficient caretaker of children. It's the family 
that seems a little nuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Wilson and Victor Garber play parents who claim to have  
three children: Doc, Maggie and Sam. But Maggie is imaginary. 
</P>
<P>
	The psycho-drama explores why the mother maintains the fantasy,  
and why her family supports her in it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I liked the theme of the movie, which is that life is full of  
mysteries, and you never know why people do things,'' Miss Wilson 
says. ``It doesn't change how you feel about them, because you love 
them. I liked the fact that the story wasn't pat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The actress has enjoyed a busy couple of years. She has worked  
in feature movies: the upcoming ``Runaway Bride'' with Richard Gere 
and Julia Roberts, directed by Garry Marshall, and ``The Story of 
Us,'' with Bruce Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer, directed by Rob 
Reiner. She also appeared in the ``Psycho'' redo, in the secretary 
role originally played by Patricia Hitchcock. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kids are a little bigger, which makes it easier to work,''  
commented Miss Wilson, the mother of two. Their ages? 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't get into details like that, just because we try to  
protect their privacy,'' she said firmly. 
</P>
<P>
	Her caution is perhaps natural. Her husband and the father of  
the children is Tom Hanks, who has two best-actor Oscars and is up 
for another for ``Saving Private Ryan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Invisible Child'' originally was to be filmed in Portland,  
Ore. When the script was offered to Miss Wilson, she replied: ``I'd 
love to do this, but Tom and I try not to work at the same time, 
and he's doing a movie.'' The Lifetime people did some rearranging, 
and filming was moved to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	When one is working, the other brings the kids on location for  
extended visits. Miss Wilson and the children joined Hanks during 
the long spells on location for ``Saving Private Ryan.'' And the 
family remained together when she worked in New York on ``Mixed 
Nuts'' with Steve Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	They know first-hand the perils wrought by separation on  
location. They met in 1985 when they co-starred in ``Volunteers,'' 
one of Hanks' more forgettable endeavors. They married after his 
1987 divorce from Samantha Lewes. As part of their togetherness 
policy, they have appeared in ``Bonfire of the Vanities,'' 
``Sleepless in Seattle,'' ``That Thing You Do'' (which Hanks wrote 
and directed), and in his 12-part HBO series, ``From the Earth to 
the Moon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Staying together ``is a problem only if it's not discussed, only  
if people pretend it's not going to create a problem,'' she said. 
``You have to be honest and work it out, you have to schedule 
things, and sometimes you'll have to give up some things. It's not 
that hard -- if you're honest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Is Hanks' all-round-decent-guy image for real? Does he ever get  
cranky in the morning or snap at the kids? 
</P>
<P>
	His wife contemplated the questions for a moment, then replied,  
laughing: ``Well, let's just say he's human.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Wilson grew up in Hollywood. On her first day at Hollywood  
High, she was photographed for Harper's Bazaar, which was doing a 
feature on high schoolers. That got her an agent. Then she 
accompanied a cheerleader friend to an audition for ``The Brady 
Bunch'' and she was chosen for a role, which got her into the 
Screen Actors Guild. 
</P>
<P>
	Her first substantial acting role was in ``Happy Days,'' the  
1970s TV sitcom. 
</P>
<P>
	In an otherwise slow start to her career, Miss Wilson appeared  
in a flock of TV commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great job,'' she recalls. ``It always made me laugh  
when actors said, `I won't do commercials.' I just never understood 
that. First of all, people don't really recognize you. I wouldn't 
do tacky things, products I didn't believe in. 
</P>
<P>
	``You name it, I've done it. I did a gazillion Burger King,  
McDonald's, car commercials, coffee commercials. They paid the 
rent.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 09:12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins' Manager Has Uphill Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) -- Step inside the office of the Florida  
Marlins' manager and notice change in the air. It's no longer 
filled with expletives or the smell of cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	Chain-smoking, chain-cursing Jim Leyland has departed for the  
Colorado Rockies, taking along his bad habits and leaving behind a 
bad team. That's where John Boles comes in. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999 Marlins will probably be bad again, but better. And  
while last year's 108 losses wore on Leyland to the point where he 
could take no more, new manager Boles is braced for the 
tribulations of rebuilding baseball's worst team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I refuse to get frustrated or depressed about anything,''  
Boles said. ``If I'm going to have moments like that, they're going 
to be behind these four walls by myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marlins players and officials consider the 50-year-old manager a  
perfect fit for a young team listed as a million-to-1 shot to win 
the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Boles has a sense of humor -- which he'll need -- and an  
irrepressible optimism. When it comes to proven major league 
talent, Boles sees the Marlins' clubhouse as half-full rather than 
half-empty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody in this business is negative,'' he said. ``Everybody  
talks about what a guy can't do. Why don't we spend more time 
talking about his strengths rather than his weaknesses?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In that spirit, let's downplay the challenge Boles faces in  
replacing a manager who has 996 career victories. Instead, let's 
note that Boles is the only skipper in the Marlins' six-season 
history with a winning career record. 
</P>
<P>
	He went 40-35 for Florida in the second half of 1996 after Rene  
Lachemann was fired. Around the country, Boles is remembered for a 
wide-eyed look in the dugout that became a familiar sight on ESPN 
highlights. He joked that he resembled comedian Marty Feldman, but 
nobody laughed about the way Boles stabilized an underachieving 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very positive experience,'' he said. ``Not to pat  
myself on the back, but I did feel good about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the season, Boles knew the Marlins were on the  
verge of title contention. But when general manager David 
Dombrowski had a chance to hire Leyland, Boles graciously stepped 
aside and returned to his former position as vice president of 
player development. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an unusual situation that John dealt with as well as  
anybody possibly could,'' Dombrowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boles knew the depth of Leyland's credentials, and thought the  
Marlins were fortunate to be able to get him. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best thing anybody ever said to me was that I'm a company  
man,'' Boles said. '' People look at it in a negative way. I think 
it's the best thing you can say about a person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Leyland, the Marlins won the 1997 World Series. Then came  
the dismantling, capped by Leyland's departure after last season. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one manager with a World Series ring was interested in  
the job, but Dombrowski wanted Boles, who signed a three-year 
contract in October. 
</P>
<P>
	Boles has paid his dues. The Chicago native never played  
professional baseball, but he was a minor league manager from 1981 
to 1986 in such outposts as Appleton, Buffalo and Omaha. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Kansas City Royals wanted Boles to help with player  
development, he switched to the administrative side in 1986. He 
became the Marlins' director of player development in November 
1991, 18 months before the first game in franchise history. 
</P>
<P>
	As the former head of the Florida farm system, Boles knows most  
of the players in camp this spring. Youngsters Mark Kotsay, Ryan 
Dempster and Luis Castillo rave about him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm much more relaxed this spring,'' said Castillo, trying to  
win the starting job at second base. ``He knows me, and he's 
followed me a long time. There's a lot less pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boles thought his career path would lead to a job as general  
manager, but instead he finds himself back in the dugout. That's 
where the company needs him, and that's fine with Boles. 
</P>
<P>
	He bought new glasses for his new job, hoping he won't appear so  
wide-eyed this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Marty Feldman look is leaving,'' he said, adjusting the  
glasses. ``With these on, it hides some flaws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's what managing the Marlins will be all about: hiding  
flaws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
