<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Joe Camel's Creator Speaks Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- Joe Camel was designed to appeal to young  
adults, not children, the character's creator says. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Beasley, a marketing executive for R.J. Reynolds Tobacco  
Co., said she rejected plans to give the cartoon character a 
punk-style haircut or to show him skating or skateboarding. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio labor union trust funds are suing several major tobacco  
companies in federal court for nearly $2 billion to cover the costs 
of treating workers for smoking-related illnesses. Beasley 
testified Friday; the trial resumes this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Union lawyers contend that Joe Camel was created to attract  
young smokers who were switching to other brands. They said the 
character was more recognizable than Ronald McDonald among 
consumers ages 10 to 17. 
</P>
<P>
	James Morgan, who was president and CEO at Philip Morris until  
he retired in 1997, denied claims that the companies tried to get 
young customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cost of being accused of marketing to minors dwarfs any  
profits you could ever make,'' Morgan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
