<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 06:26:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Evidence May Enter Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A federal judge has barred lawyers for  
Whitewater figure Susan McDougal from presenting evidence of 
``prosecutorial vindictiveness'' during her trial next week on 
criminal contempt and obstruction charges. 
</P>
<P>
	However, U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. on Friday did not  
rule out letting Mrs. McDougal present evidence of ``misconduct'' 
by the government or by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr in his 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges against Mrs. McDougal relate to her testimony in the  
Whitewater probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand jurors were investigating whether Mrs. McDougal had  
improper financial dealings with President Clinton and Hillary 
Rodham Clinton when he was governor of Arkansas. McDougal and the 
Clintons were business partners in the failed real estate 
development known as Whitewater. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal has said she refused to answer questions because  
she believes Starr would twist her words to suit his purposes and 
may charge her with perjury if he doesn't get the testimony he 
wants. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources have said defense lawyers were considering calling  
Monica Lewinsky to testify about her experiences with Starr. Ms. 
Lewinsky has described one of Starr's prosecutors as a ``revolting 
specimen of humanity'' and another as a ``pit-bull terrier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Howard ruled he wouldn't permit evidence of  
``vindictiveness,'' he deferred a decision on whether to permit 
evidence of misconduct, specifically whether Starr wanted Mrs. 
McDougal to lie about the business dealings of the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyer Mark Geragos of Los Angeles would not say Friday  
whom he would call as witnesses, but he did characterize the ruling 
as a victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will attempt to show a pattern by this guy ... Starr and  
his office ... to go through and wreak havoc in people's lives and 
just make them so miserable and threaten them so badly and scare 
them so much that they will say whatever it is he wants them to 
say,'' Geragos said. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Independent Counsel Hickman Ewing Jr. said testimony from  
Ms. Lewinsky would be irrelevant to the case and the prosecution 
would fight such an effort. Ewing also considered irrelevant what 
Mrs. McDougal thinks of Starr's behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously from our standpoint, we want to keep the jury  
focused on the real issues of the trial,'' Ewing said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
