<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abilene Christian Wins Track Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Delloreen Ennis-London captured her fourth  
NCAA title in the 55-meter hurdles Saturday, helping Abilerne 
Christian to a sweep of the men's and women's titles in the NCAA 
Division II Track and Field Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Ennis-London led from the first hurdle en route to setting an  
NCAA Division II record of 7.62 seconds. The old record of 7.67 was 
set in 1994 by Sherlese Taylor of St. Augustine's. 
</P>
<P>
	Abilene Christian swept the event with Suzanee Dickenson and  
Shawntel Newhouse finishing second and third at 7.86 and 7.95. 
</P>
<P>
	The sweep helped the Wildcats set a meet record with 119 points,  
more than the combined total of the next three teams. Abilene 
Christian's men won the championship for a fourth straight year, 
accumulating 85 points, its sixth title in seven years. St 
Augustine was second with 50 points and Morehouse College took 
third with 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Ennis-London had no time to rest after hurdling, returning to  
the track less than five minutes later to finish second in the 
55-meter dash in 6.95. Humbolt State's Trinity Davis won in 6.94. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad that I broke the record, but there is always room for  
improvement,'' Ennis-London said, adding that the quick turnaround 
may have deprived her of being a double winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is hardly enough time in between. If I had five or 10  
minutes I would have done better.'' she said, adding that during 
the break and before the event she tried to ``stay away from the 
crowd ... pray and listen to Reggae music. It helps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the seventh straight NCAA women's indoor title and 11th  
in 12 years for Abilene Christian. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew we had a really strong team and I thought we'd win, but  
it wasn't expected that we would do this well,'' Abiliene Christian 
coach Wes Kittley said. ``We really dominated up top. You dream 
that it can happen like this and today it did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abilene Christian also swept the triple jump, with Renna Toniste  
winning at 40-9, followed by Hillerie Shelton and Dawnyel Newhouse 
took third. 
</P>
<P>
	St Augustine finished second with 44 points, while Adams State  
earned third with 32. 
</P>
<P>
	Another record was set by Lewis freshman Lana Jekabsone, who  
lowered tbe 800 mark of 2:07.08 set by Stacey Mill of Adams State 
in 1997. Jekabsone won the race in 2:06.00. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas A&AMP;M-Kingsville's Matt Hickl went 18-1. breaking the pole  
vault record of 18-0 1/4 set by Dustin DeRosier of St. Cloud State in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	South Dakota's Nic Burrow won the mile in 4:03.71, breaking the  
mark of 4:04.76 set by Abilene Christian's Musa Gwanzura last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Abilene Christian's winners included Terrance Woods in the men's  
triple jump at 52-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 14:12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hubert Pops Into Winston Cup Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- At the first two Winston Cup races off 1998,  
Tom Hubert was changing tires. In Sunday's Las Vegas 400, he'll be 
starting fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	After Hubert suddenly popped into the upper reaches of the speed  
chart with his surprising qualifying lap Friday at Las Vegas Motor 
Speedway, the biggest question in among the media covering the race 
was: ``Who is this guy?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually during the week I work for the 22 car,'' said Hubert,  
referring to the Pontiac driven by Ward Burton. ``On the weekends, 
I change tires for Steve Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just kind of a part-time deal until they get some  
things straightened out, but this weekend we're not doing any of 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hubert, a 34-year-old Californian now living near Charlotte,  
N.C., says he has driven only a ``handful of races'' since 1987. 
This will be only his fourth Winston Cup start, and his first on an 
oval after three road races. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be interesting to get in a weekly situation and see  
what we could do,'' Hubert said. ``Hopefully, this will help get 
something going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, his Winston Cup plans call for three races with car  
owner Bradford White, including the road race in Sonoma, Calif., 
and an oval event at Michigan Speedway. He's also close to a deal 
to run the entire NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can get more sponsor money for this, we'll run the Cup  
car as many times as we can,'' Hubert said. 
</P>
<P>
	He has a simple plan.  
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest thing for me is just to run all day and not cause  
any of these guys any problems.'' Hubert said. ``They're in the big 
deal, and we're here to learn. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're capable to run with them, we will. But, hopefully,  
we'll be smart enough to get out of the way when we need to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, he'll go back to work as a crewman when he gets home.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll go back to work for the 22,'' Hubert said. ``Park's deal,  
if they need me, I'll still keep changing tires. They've got 
someone else over there now that's going to do it this weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	MISSING IN ACTION: Among the nine drivers who failed to make the  
43-car field for Sunday's race were series regulars Kyle Petty, Ted 
Musgrave and Dave Marcis. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five drivers qualified on Friday and 11 more made it into  
the lineup by standing on their first-day laps. Rusty Wallace, Dale 
Earnhardt, Jimmy Spencer, Ernie Irvan, Steve Park and rookie 
Stanton Barrett all made it as provisionals, based on last year's 
car owner points. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrell Waltrip got the final spot, the third straight race he  
has had to fall back on the former series champion's provisional. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a first for me,'' said Musgrave, in his first season  
with car owner Butch Mock. ``It's very disgusting. We saved the car 
and came back in the second round and we're fastest in the second 
round. But as slow as the racetrack got today, nobody made it 
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	GOOD OPPORTUNITY: Mike Skinner, who heads into the Las Vegas  
race leading the Winston Cup points, likes his chances of getting 
his first series win on the 1 1/2, nearly-flat oval. 
</P>
<P>
	One part of his reasoning is his success at Twin Ring Motegi,  
the oval track in Japan where Skinner has won two straight fall 
exhibition races. 
</P>
<P>
	``Las Vegas has some similarities to the Japan track,'' he said.  
``It's flat, fast, long and smooth. It's a place I think that my 
Chevrolet has a good chance of running good.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 16:12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Free House Wins Big 'Cap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Free House, often overshadowed by Silver  
Charm, beat the 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner and four 
others Saturday in the $1 million Santa Anita Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	Free House, a 5-year-old colt who went off at 4-1, proved the  
best of one of the finest Big 'Cap fields in years, finishing a 
half-length in front. Event of the Year was second and Silver Charm 
wound up another half-length behind in third. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Chris McCarron, Free House opened a slight lead in the  
turn for home, then held off challenges by Event of the Year and 
Silver Charm down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was the ninth of Free House's 21-race career, and  
the son of Smokester is now 3-for-5 in eight career meetings with 
Silver Charm. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was the second straight for Silver Charm, who finished  
a badly beaten third behind winner Puerto Madero in the Jan. 30 
Donn Handicap at Gulfstream. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Madero, the second choice in the Big 'Cap wagering,  
wasn't able to duplicate his Donn victory, finishing fifth at Santa 
Anita. 
</P>
<P>
	Free House carried 123 pounds, one less than high weight Silver  
Charm, and was clocked in 2:00 3-5 for 1 1/4 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner paid $10.20, $5.20 and $2.80. Event of the Year,  
ridden by Corey Nakatani and carrying 119, paid $5.40 and $2.80. 
The show payoff on Silver Charm, with Gary Stevens up, was $2.20. 
</P>
<P>
	The horses were virtually stride for stride through most of the  
race, with Free House either in the lead or just off it. 
</P>
<P>
	Event of the Year and Silver Charm also were near the front the  
entire way, and so were in good position for the stretch run. But 
Free House, on the inside, finished strongly. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr Fong was fourth, with Sidon last in the six-horse field.  
</P>
<P>
	Winner of the Santa Anita Derby and San Felipe Stakes two years  
ago, Free House was coming off a neck victory over Malek, last 
year's Big 'Cap winner, in the San Antonio Handicap on Feb. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was worth $600,000 for Free House's owners, Trudy  
McCaffery and John Toffan, and the horse has now earned more than 
$3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm has won 12 of 22 career starts and has finished out  
of the money just once. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0094 </DOCNO>
