<DOCNO> APW19990306.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 00:12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Controversy Surrounds Mass. HMOs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Prompted by the loud complaints of senior  
citizens, Massachusetts' secretary of state has given health 
maintenance organizations three weeks to convince him they really 
are nonprofits. 
</P>
<P>
	If they fail, the matter could be referred for court action  
barring the companies from doing business. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary William Galvin's demand on Thursday followed the  
decision of several HMOs to stop providing unlimited prescription 
coverage to seniors. 
</P>
<P>
	Until recently, the state was the only one in the nation to  
require such coverage, but a federal judge in Boston ruled in 
October that HMOs needn't provide it. 
</P>
<P>
	The insurers have implemented limited drug benefits and special  
plans to help lower-income people pay for their drugs, but 
activists say the elderly are still hurting. An estimated 10,000 
will end up paying more for their health-sustaining prescriptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Mula, 72, of Hudson, said he expects to spend $1,700 more  
this year on prescription drugs for his wife Isabelle, who has 
congestive heart failure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel the United States government, the drug industry and the  
medical industry are not taking care of their seniors,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The HMOs blame Medicare for failing to adequately reimburse  
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the secretary's frustration is misplaced. He's  
confusing the issues,'' said Karen Ignagni, president of the 
American Association of Health Plans. 
</P>
<P>
	It was far from certain the state attorney general would put  
teeth into Galvin's threat, and Galvin himself admits his power is 
limited. But he says he's acting because thousands of Medicare HMO 
patients are suffering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 11:11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Wins World Cup Downhill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KVITFJELL, Norway (AP) -- Andreas Schifferer of Austria won his  
second World Cup downhill in two days Saturday while Lasse Kjus of 
Norway finished second, helping his bid for the overall title. 
</P>
<P>
	Schifferer was timed in 1 minute, 46.78 seconds. Kjus was .18  
second back and helped his chances in a three-way race for the 
overall championship with leader Kjetil Andre Aamodt of Norway and 
defending champion Hermann Maier of Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	Maier chances dimmed with an 11th place finish after an even  
more disappointing 16th on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt was fifth in Saturday's downhill, but he picked up enough  
points to keep his overall lead with 1,235 to 1,219 for Kjus. Maier 
was third with 1,142. 
</P>
<P>
	A super-G was scheduled for Sunday with the final round of  
season races to begin Wednesday in Sierra Nevada, Spain, where the 
overall title will be decided. 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt said he fears his friend and teammate Kjus more than the  
Maier, the ``Herminator''. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kjus is going to be the toughest competitor, and he gained  
many points on me today. It's going to be one of us,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus, who clinched the World Cup downhill title Friday, called  
the race even. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kjetil is going to be tough, but so is Maier. We're about  
equal,'' Kjus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schifferer has a chance of taking second in the downhill overall  
standings with one more race to go. He vaulted from sixth to third 
place ending up with 398 points. He is 13 points behind teammate 
Werner Franz, who finished eighth Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
