<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 11:31:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Hamilton Had Track Tryout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Every winter, Colorado Rockies outfielder  
Darryl Hamilton relives his version of the Olympic dream, settling 
into the starting blocks with sprinters Carl Lewis and LeRoy 
Burrell. 
</P>
<P>
	It's often a humbling experience for Hamilton as he receives a  
yearly reminder that stealing bases and patrolling center field is 
a lot different than keeping up with the world's fastest men. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still in awe of those guys,'' Hamilton said. ``I'm sitting  
there thinking after I did it, `Wow! I had Carl Lewis to my left! I 
had LeRoy Burrell to my right!' Not too many people can say that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The workouts are part the offseason training program Hamilton  
started in 1995 when his brother recommended he improve his 
mechanics and flexibility in hopes of avoiding injuries that dogged 
him for two straight seasons with the Milwaukee Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton has returned to the Houston to train with the  
prestigious Santa Monica Track Club every winter since, marking one 
of the few constants in his professional life as he goes through 
spring training with his fourth team in five seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking for a leadoff hitter to roam center field in expansive  
Coors Field, the Rockies acquired Hamilton in a July 31 trade that 
sent Ellis Burks to San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton never saw the trade coming. When it did, his immediate  
reaction was one of revenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love those guys to death over there, but I was thinking that  
the best thing I could do is make it so they don't go (to the 
playoffs),'' Hamilton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton got his chance as the Giants came to Denver for a  
season-ending three game series with the Rockies. After winning the 
first two games, San Francisco needed one more victory to win the 
NL Wild Card. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were talking about that in the training room the week  
before the actual game,'' Hamilton said. ``I told them, `Man, I've 
got a feeling we're going to lose the first two games. It's going 
to get down to the last day, and we're going to win and we're going 
to break their hearts.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	The premonition came true as the Rockies erased a seven-run  
deficit to beat San Francisco, and the Giants lost a one-game 
playoff to the Chicago Cubs the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton tormented his former team with two hits in the season  
finale, completing an impressive two-month run with the Rockies. 
After the trade, he hit .335 with five homers, 25 RBIs and 30 runs 
scored, prompting Colorado to re-sign him after the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone put the emphasis on me being in a situation where I  
was trying out for the Rockies, but basically it was the other way 
around,'' Hamilton said. ``I was feeling things out and trying to 
decide if this is where I want to be. If I felt weird or 
uncomfortable about the situation, I wouldn't have come back. I 
felt good about the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies' feelings are mutual. Burks was ill-suited for  
center field, and his predecessors form a forgettable list that 
includes Alex Cole and Mike Kingery. 
</P>
<P>
	Though some fans bristled when Colorado didn't go after bigger  
free-agent names such as Bernie Williams, Devon White, Brian Jordan 
and Steve Finley, Rockies general manager Bob Gebhard feels the 
best man was also the closest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bringing him back sometimes gets lost in the shuffle,''  
Gebhard said. ``We had him for two months and he's huge. We have a 
tough center field to play. Darryl's a professional center fielder, 
and he's a leadoff guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With their powerful lineup, the Rockies are a leadoff hitters  
dream. If Hamilton can come close to matching last year's .398 
on-base percentage, he has an excellent chance to score 100 runs 
for the first time in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of those runs are sure to come as Hamilton jogs around the  
bases ahead of home runs hit by Larry Walker, Dante Bichette and 
Vinny Castilla. 
</P>
<P>
	He can save the sprinting for the offseason.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
