<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Robert Irwin    	
</P>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- Robert Irwin, three-time winner of the  
horse training title at Oaklawn Park, died Saturday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin won Oaklawn championships in 1965, 1966 and 1968. He  
retired from training and joined Oaklawn as a paddock guard in 
1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Five times, Irwin finished in the top 10 nationally in the  
number of races won. 

</P>
<P>
 *John Kennelly    	
</P>
<P>
	RIDGEWOOD, N.J. (AP) -- Sportscaster John Kennelly, a longtime  
host of the Giants' pregame show on New York's WNEW-AM radio, 
Friday after a long illness. He was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a sportscaster in Baltimore before joining WCBS-AM in New  
York as a newscaster in the early 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennelly became WNEW's sports director a few years later and was  
host of the station's Giants pregame show from the mid-1970s 
through 1991. He became a sports anchor with WBBR-AM and Bloomberg 
Television after leaving WNEW. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, three sons, and four brothers.  

</P>
<P>
 *Mary Dalton    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Mary Dalton, who with her husband donated  
200 pieces of art to the Mint Museum of Charlotte, died Thursday. 
She was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Dalton and her late husband built a multimillion-dollar art and  
rare book collection and gave most of it away to institutions 
around the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Their collection of American and European art was once  
considered the state's finest collection, public or private. A wing 
bearing their names was built before their donation. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry Dalton, a successful banker and textile executive, died in  
1990 at age 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Museums and universities around the Southeast bear their  
generosity. There's the Dalton Rare Book room at Duke University, 
where Harry Dalton graduated, and the Dalton Art Gallery at Agnes 
Scott College in Georgia, where Mrs. Dalton attended. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters in 1982 rejected a bond issue to pay for an expansion of  
the Mint Museum, prompting the Daltons to offer much of their 
collection to the museum if a wing could be built to house it. 
Voters passed a bond issue and the museum raised money to fund the 
wing. 

</P>
<P>
                         *William McGonagle    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Retired Navy Capt. William L. McGonagle, who  
received the Medal of Honor for heroism as skipper of the USS 
Liberty when Israel unleashed a deadly attack on the 
intelligence-gathering ship in 1967, died Wednesday. He was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-four crewmen were killed and 171 were wounded when the  
Liberty was attacked by Israeli air force planes and torpedo boats 
in international waters north of Sinai during the Six Day War 
between Israel and its Arab neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	The ship was bombed with napalm, torpedoed and shelled.  
</P>
<P>
	The attack, blamed on a mistaken identification of the Liberty  
as an Egyptian ship, remains one of the most controversial events 
in U.S.-Israeli relations and led to allegations of a cover-up by 
the governments. 
</P>
<P>
	McGonagle, who was severely wounded but stayed in command on the  
bridge through the battle and for many hours afterward, broke his 
silence years later and joined former shipmates in demanding the 
two governments release all details of the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel apologized to the United States but claimed there had  
been a misidentification and that the ship's markings were 
inadequate. Israel paid more than $12 million in compensation. 

</P>
<P>
 *Sheik Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa,    	
</P>
<P>
	MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- Sheik Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa, the emir  
of Bahrain, died Saturday of a heart attack shortly after a meeting 
with Defense Secretary William Cohen. He was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheik Isa, who ruled for 38 years, was buried within hours, with  
thousands of Bahrainis showering the 12-mile funeral route with 
flowers in a traditional display of mourning. 
</P>
<P>
	His son, Sheik Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa, assumed the throne.  
Cohen and his entourage left for Saudi Arabia shortly after the 
emir's death. 
</P>
<P>
	He is the second pro-Western Arab leader to die in two months,  
following the death of Jordan's King Hussein in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Bahrain, a nation of 35 islands covering 260 square miles, is  
home to the biggest U.S. naval presence in the region. Sheik Isa 
allowed British and American warplanes to use Bahraini airfields 
during the 1991 Persian Gulf War. Afterward, he traveled to 
Washington and signed a security pact with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton offered his condolences to the people of  
Bahrain and said the emir will be missed. 
</P>
<P>
	About 2,500 Americans live and work in Bahrain, including about  
1,000 in the military. U.S. warships often dock in Bahrain, home to 
the 5th Fleet, so sailors can take shore leave. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheik Isa had offered the facilities to the Navy, discreetly at  
first fearing popular resentment against a foreign military 
presence. During and after the 1990-91 Gulf crisis, he became more 
open about the U.S. presence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
