<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Apparent Haiti Smuggling Boats Sink  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Two boats carrying as many as 43 Haitians in an  
apparent bid to smuggle them into the United States sank today off 
the South Florida coast, and rescuers found only three survivors. 
The Coast Guard recovered the bodies of two men and saw two other 
bodies sink below the surface. Three men rescued off West Palm 
Beach told U.S. Border Patrol officers that one boat -- carrying 18 
Haitians -- broke down and that the other boat -- carrying between 18 
to 25 more refugees -- came to help out. Both boats then went under, 
they said. 

</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians Vow to Sign Pact  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have vowed to sign a  
peace plan tomorrow to give them autonomy, the Clinton 
administration said today. The Serbs face the threat of NATO 
airstrikes if they refuse to sign the deal and if they continue a 
military buildup. The Serbs have accepted most of the political 
aspects of the peace plan to give broad self-rule to Kosovo for the 
next three years. But Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has 
rejected allowing a 30,000-member, NATO-led peacekeeping force to 
police the deal. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Wants Colombian Killers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House demanded today that a  
Colombian rebel group turn over those responsible for the 
kidnapping and murder of three Americans found dead in Venezuela. 
``We are outraged by the murders,'' White House press secretary Joe 
Lockhart said. ``We have strong indications they were kidnapped and 
murdered by members of the Colombian rebel group'' known as the 
Revolutionary Armed Force of Colombia, Lockhart said. 

</P>
<P>
	Sinn Fein Invited to Belfast Talks  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The Protestant leader charged  
with forming Northern Ireland's new government said today he has 
invited the senior Sinn Fein leaders to urgent talks, the first 
time he's done so. Although Ulster Unionist Party leader David 
Trimble began talking with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams six months 
ago, until now such contact has always been at the behest of the 
Irish Republican Army-allied party. Trimble's invitation comes as 
the deadline set by the British government approaches to hand back 
power to local politicians in accord with last year's peace 
agreement. 

</P>
<P>
	Khmer Rouge Army Chief Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- The last senior leader of the Khmer  
Rouge guerrilla army was arrested today and flown to Phnom Penh, 
where authorities said he will face trial for his alleged role in a 
regime that killed up to 2 million people. Soldiers captured Ta 
Mok, known as ``The Butcher'' for his ruthlessness, near the 
northern border with Thailand, senior Cambodian generals said. The 
guerrilla chief topped the most-wanted list of senior Khmer Rouge 
figures after the death last year of the movement's leader, Pol 
Pot. 

</P>
<P>
	Protesters Target The Gap, Nike  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Protesters across the country demonstrated today  
outside stores they say sell clothing made in sweatshop conditions. 
Several hundred activists marched up Manhattan's Fifth Avenue to 
the Nike store on East 57th Street. In San Francisco, as many as 
300 activists crowded in front of the Gap flagship store. Other 
anti-Gap protests happened in front of Northern California stores 
in Berkeley, Fresno, Santa Monica and Santa Barbara. In Cambridge, 
Mass., about 10 Harvard University students protested outside The 
Gap there. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Visit Central America  
</P>
<P>
	POSOLTEGA, Nicaragua (AP) -- President Clinton and first lady  
Hillary Rodham Clinton will travel to Nicaragua on Monday to begin 
a four-day tour of the countries hardest hit by Hurricane Mitch. 
They will visit Honduras, El Salvador and Guatemala. Mitch, which 
killed more than 9,000 people, left hundreds of thousands homeless 
and caused billions of dollars in damage. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 3 UConn Tops No. 10 St. John's  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Connecticut won its second straight Big East  
tournament title with an 82-63 victory over 10th-ranked St. John's 
tonight. It was their third championship in the last four years and 
their fourth of the '90s, twice what any other school managed in 
that time. The Huskies' (28-2) win over the Red Storm (24-8) at 
Madison Square Garden ended any doubts about the Huskies being a 
No. 1 seed in the NCAA tournament. 

</P>
<P>
	Austin Scores 23 As Magic Win  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Ike Austin scored a season-high 23 points  
as Orlando stopped Detroit's six-game winning streak, winning 87-82 
tonight. The Magic, which has won four straight, improved the best 
record in the Eastern Conference to 14-4, including a 10-0 mark at 
Orlando Arena. Grant Hill led Detroit with 17 points. Jerry 
Stackhouse and Bison Dele each had 15. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  

