<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sotheby's Auctions 'Mulan' Artwork </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cartoons from Disney's film ``Mulan'' hit the  
auction block at Sotheby's on Saturday and danced past pre-sale 
estimates as the animation art brought in more than $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd of buyers cheered as an animated image of the villain  
Shan Yu and his falcon sold for $43,700 -- much higher than its 
estimated value of $1,200. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone loves a good villain,'' said auctioneer David N.  
Redden, responding to the applause. 
</P>
<P>
	The forbidding image shows Shan Yu's falcon, his wings  
outstretched, coming to perch on his master's arm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had just started a villains room in my house ... and Shan Yu  
is perfect for it,'' said Heide R. Fowler, a private collector from 
Austin, Texas who was the winning bidder. 
</P>
<P>
	The items for sale were all original animation art cell setups,  
which feature the actual hand-painted backgrounds or production 
overlays used in the making of the film. 
</P>
<P>
	While auction lots normally sell in fewer than 30 seconds, the  
bidding for Shan Yu lasted several tense minutes, going back and 
forth between Fowler and a telephone bidder. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was sort of like a tennis match,'' said Sotheby's spokesman  
Matt Robbins. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 film chronicles the adventures of a young woman whose  
irrepressible spirit clashes with Chinese traditional society. 
</P>
<P>
	Other highlights of the auction included the image of Mulan and  
her love interest, Captain Shang, which surpassed pre-sale 
estimates of $2,000, selling for $39,100. 
</P>
<P>
	A miniature of the dragon Mushu, estimated at $1,800, went for  
$14,950. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale, which took in $507,000, also featured illustrations  
from the Disney storybooks in mediums ranging from watercolor, pen, 
and pencil. 
</P>
<P>
	The record for sales of animation artwork belongs to another  
Disney film: Sales from ``The Lion King'' totaled nearly $2 million 
at Sotheby's in 1995. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
