<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alanis: Being Famous Not Worth It </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Alanis Morissette is questioning the value of  
fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I've gone from repression to explosion to  
contemplation,'' Morissette says in the April issue of Spin 
magazine. ``I always believed in black and white; something was 
either great or horrible, including myself. And now it's just 
gray.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following the overwhelming success of her 1995 album ``Jagged  
Little Pill,'' Morissette took a lengthy recording break to find 
herself, studying yoga, spending time at a nudist colony and 
reading self-help books. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't always that way for the 24-year-old who started  
singing professionally as a girl in Canada, and recently released 
her second major album ``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very intrigued by what celebrity status, fame, adulation  
could bring me,'' she says. ``It was touted as something that would 
raise your self-esteem and provide you with eternal happiness. Food 
would taste better, people would be more exciting, relationships 
would be great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She found that wasn't true.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wish people could achieve what they think would give them  
happiness in order for them to realize that that's not the way that 
happiness can be found,'' she says, acknowledging that her success 
and wealth makes such judgments suspect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get `easy for her to say' all the time,'' she says. ``It is  
much easier for me to say.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990306.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 09:05:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Dream Home' Has Few Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAND FORKS, N.D. (AP) --Christa and Steve Larson's new home has  
almost everything they wanted -- big kitchen with new appliances, 
two bedrooms, open living room with picture window. What's missing 
are neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	Houses are all around, but in their immediate four-square-block  
neighborhood, only three others are occupied. The yards are only 
partly sodded. The windows have no curtains and ``For Sale'' signs 
are everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``We love it here,'' Christa Larson says. ``But, yes, of course  
we would love to have neighbors. It's TOO quiet, sometimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After flood and fire ravaged the city in 1997, two new  
subdivisions with 193 houses were built in a hurry, with the help 
of federal grant money. 
</P>
<P>
	But even after offers of free snowblowers, lawn mowers and an  
allowance of up to $5,000 for appliances, 180 of the homes in the 
Congressional 1 and Congressional 2 subdivisions remain vacant. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics complain the homes are too near trailer courts and that  
schools and supermarkets are too far away. Many say the prices -- 
ranging from $105,000 to $145,000 -- are too high. And most grumble 
that the subdivisions' names, echoing government-issue housing, put 
some buyers off. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took time to buy the land and get the houses started,''  
said Grand Forks area planner Floyd Hickok. ``By the time they 
became available, most of the people displaced by the flood had 
made other arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, ``most of the houses that were lost in the  
flood were in the $50,000 to $80,000 range, 50-year-old houses. 
There's no way that you can build new for anywhere near that 
price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Real estate agents, city officials and Grand Forks Homes, the  
non-profit agency in charge of the development, all say they have 
put their squabbles behind them to focus on sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think our biggest concern was that we were not involved in  
the process early on,'' said Janelle Kerr, president of the Grand 
Forks Board of Realtors. ``But we have really taken a proactive 
view, as everyone has, that the important thing now is to be part 
of the solution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We know something needs to be done,'' said Mayor Pat Owens.  
``In hindsight, would we have done things differently in the 
beginning? Absolutely. But at the time, all we knew is there was a 
demand for homes and private builders weren't interested in taking 
the risk of building on their own, so somebody had to step in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1997, the City Council approved the purchase of 50  
acres of open fields on the west side of town with $4 million in 
federal grant money. 
</P>
<P>
	To head the project, the city called on the expertise of Grand  
Forks Homes, an eight-member board of people appointed by local 
churches that builds housing for low- and moderate-income families. 
</P>
<P>
	The city sold the land to Grand Forks Homes for $12,000 per acre  
and approved $10.15 million in bonds to build up to 200 houses. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Keeley, a Grand Forks Homes board member, said he was  
skeptical of the project in the beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first, I resisted it,'' he said. ``I didn't think it was  
our position as a non-profit housing group to be in the business of 
building 200 new homes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But private contractors didn't step forward, Keeley said, and he  
became convinced people would buy the homes. Grand Forks Homes did 
a survey that found 176 property owners interested in buying a 
house for about $125,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Keeley still doesn't understand why the homes are not selling.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a mystery to me. But there has been an incredible amount  
of badmouthing about the project, talk of bad construction and poor 
quality, that kind of thing,'' Keeley said. ``We feel that 
virtually everything being said is either untrue or unfair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larson, who still hasn't completely unpacked since moving in two  
months ago, agrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of people who badmouth the houses haven't even  
been out to see them,'' she said. ``People told us the same thing, 
`Oh, you don't want to buy one of those homes. They're not quality 
built.' But I think our house is fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Larsons are not Grand Forks flood victims. They moved from  
Fargo to take new jobs with local hotels. Their two-bedroom house 
in Congressional 1, which cost $119,000, came with an unfinished 
basement, but Larson's father and stepfather are filling it with a 
second bathroom, a third bedroom, a family room and a den. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like the fact that we can put our own finishing touches on  
it,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	While people drive through the subdivisions looking at the  
homes, serious inquiries are still rare. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand Forks Homes plans to ask the City Council to approve $10.4  
million more in grant money, half of it for maintenance expenses 
and half to offer more incentives to lure buyers. The non-profit 
has also arranged for a local radio station to give away one of the 
houses as a ``dream home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keeley is confident the homes will sell quickly if the  
incentives are approved. But he said word of the incentives may 
also be to blame for stalled sales right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one's going to buy a home today if they think they'll get a  
better deal in a couple weeks,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Larson, whose only incentives were a new snowblower and kitchen  
appliances, said she supports more incentives if it means she'll 
have neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd open up my door any time to someone who wanted to look at  
my house,'' she said. ``We want this to be a neighborhood, and that 
takes people.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
